ď*i‹qí{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "e186bd47-1bb2-4ff8-9d12-0d36b17e86aa", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.182401", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "843c3af28ad2bad6f3d4f4accea0d82c62c6ee12c51ee03892c000f770701324"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "TheMovieSearch", "rating": 6, "date": "2026-02-27", "title": null, "content": "As the seventh entry in my all time favorite horror franchise, Scream 7 arrives with enormous expectations, and I approached it as a critic rather than a lifelong Ghostface loyalist. The film still delivers an experience worth watching, but it is far from untouchable. There is admiration here, but also frustration simmering beneath the surface.\n\nSeeing Neve Campbell return carries genuine weight. Knowing the reasoning behind her comeback adds emotional texture, and her presence immediately restores a sense of legacy. With Kevin Williamson back in a prominent creative position, there is an unmistakable attempt to channel the sharp, self aware energy that defined the earlier chapters. That nostalgic current runs strongly throughout.\n\nThe incorporation of select legacy killers is one of the film's boldest swings. On paper, it is a clever reflection of modern horror culture and fan obsession. In execution, however, announcing those returns early works against the suspense. Instead of being immersed in the unfolding mystery, I found myself waiting for certain appearances rather than engaging with the present moment. The surprise factor suffers when anticipation becomes distraction.\n\nThe cast is impressively stacked, and the kill sequences are among the most brutal and meticulously staged in the franchise. The opening is explosive and instantly gripping, one of the strongest starts in recent memory. Yet the pacing begins to sag as the body count rises rapidly, creating confusion rather than sustained tension. Nostalgia repeatedly injects excitement, but it cannot fully compensate for stretches that feel slow and oddly unfocused.\n\nThere is also noticeable disservice done to several returning players, particularly one longstanding character who receives shockingly limited screen time. For a franchise built on legacy, that imbalance feels disappointing. When the story should be tightening its grip, it instead drifts, flirting with the kind of stagnation that once divided audiences during Scream 4.\n\nThe most significant stumble arrives with the Ghostface reveal. Without spoiling specifics, it is easily the most underwhelming unmasking the series has delivered. The motive feels thin, almost bafflingly so, lacking the psychological punch expected from this saga. It is a good film overall, with strong performances and intense sequences, but the ending lands with a dull echo rather than a scream. Fans may accept it, not out of satisfaction, but out of hope that an eventual eighth installment will sharpen the blade once more."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "4b600565-ef76-466e-86c5-83fefccf4dd1", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.182401", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "7a3f68d7af7c64b647377caa81f1bdc432e519967e6423737edf5d0c60883ec9"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "kjproulx", "rating": 4, "date": "2026-03-02", "title": null, "content": "The Scream franchise has always held a special place for me. The original remains one of my all-time favourite horror films, and I've generally enjoyed most of the sequels-especially the fifth and sixth entries, which I consider the strongest follow-ups to the original. Like many fans, I was genuinely excited to see Neve Campbell return to the forefront as Sidney in Scream 7. However, despite my overall goodwill toward the series (and even my mild reservations about Scream 3 being the weakest until now), I have to admit that this is the first instalment I truly disliked. To me, it stands as the weakest film in the entire franchise.\n\nThis time, the story centres on Sidney and her daughter, Tatum, who is now the same age Sidney was during the events of the first film-an idea that suggests a \"history repeating itself\" angle. Unfortunately, the execution leaves much to be desired. The motivations behind the events, as well as the way they unfold, often feel illogical and poorly justified. Without spoiling any specifics, the character decisions, twists, and reveals lack the cleverness and internal logic that the series is known for. In the days since watching it, I've struggled to piece together why many of the plot developments happen the way they do, which ultimately undermines everything.\n\nGiven that Kevin Williamson, the writer of the first, second, and fourth films, both wrote and directed this entry, my expectations were quite high. Sadly, the final product feels rushed and uneven, as though it never fully came together creatively. While Williamson's legacy with the franchise is undeniable, his limited directing experience seems to show here, resulting in a film that feels surprisingly unfocused. The signature meta commentary that once defined Scream is also noticeably diminished, and the story lacks the sharp self-awareness that once set the series apart from other slashers.\n\nThere are still flashes of what makes Scream enjoyable. A standout bar scene revisiting the \"rules\" of horror briefly captures the spirit of the franchise, but moments like this feel disconnected from the film's heavier, more melodramatic focus on Sidney's family dynamic. Tonally, the movie is inconsistent, with forced humour awkwardly inserted into an otherwise dour narrative. While there are some entertaining kills and a few fun moments with returning characters, the inclusion of AI as a central plot element ultimately creates more narrative holes than intrigue. In the end, Scream 7 isn't without redeeming qualities, but it is deeply disappointing. Fans of the series will likely still be curious enough to watch it, as I certainly would for a potential Scream 8, but for general audiences, this is one entry that can easily be skipped."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "5374567e-5789-4fc8-9820-19ce647ad58b", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.182401", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "81de9d651d76221dfac9b172d2e80747cad1e18369442a41ba4ec5e3b379ea43"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "amytude", "rating": 2, "date": "2026-02-27", "title": null, "content": "This was really bad.\n\nThe fun of figuring out The Who and why of scream movies involves actually getting to know the friend group. Loving them and being suspicious of them.\n\nThen we find out which one ( or two or three ) the killer is and why\n\nThis one we can't do that because they're bit characters that had NOTHING AT ALL TO DO WITH THE PLOT!! Just a random janitor in a hospital and the neighbor who we meet while they're having coffee and see once more on the lawn ?\n\nBecause sh read the book ?!\n\nI'm Not sure I caught why janitor man who - didn't even catch his name - was involved.\n\nWe don't get to know Tatum's friends really to care about them. They're just there and then they're all dead.\n\nMindy and Chad had nothing to do in this film Gayle and Syd seemed awkward.\n\nNothing at all worked in this.\n\nI've watched the first six movies so many times. This will go into the never to be seen again file.\n\nSimply terrible."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "1ce4ce14-c306-409d-8983-528b98c50982", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.182401", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "06bf755d3b48788a10be0056aca9de1df4ca8d1c3312eba4b66926bb3a1e71bd"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "kristianever", "rating": 4, "date": "2026-02-26", "title": null, "content": "Storyline is okay. The nostalgia part feels a bit forced (we don't really need THAT many references to the first 3 movies) but I can live with that. I don't mind Stu being just an AI, but then I was never one of those who thought he'd survived in the first movie.\n\nThe main problem here is the killer reveal. One might think the killer is related to Stu somehow as much as he uses his identity. Turns out the killer has absolutely nothing to do with Stu after all. Jessica had some killer vibes, but she lacks depth and her motive felt forced and a bit clich\u00e9, and her explanation as to why she let her son die was far from convincing. Last but not least, she only had about 10 minute screen time in the entire movie! The second killer, the doctor, was on screen for about a minute before his reveal, and his motive was not properly explained.\n\nThe murder scenes are good though, but the ideas are few. Better than Scream 5 though."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "bb4d2582-1214-43f9-a920-82000e81aa2b", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.182401", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "5c8bc1da459daef6354a6b99dc36ff8166938f5c80090274812d7d7d261028c9"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "oNerdcall", "rating": 6, "date": "2026-02-26", "title": null, "content": "Scream 7 works when it leans into its fast pace, more explicit violence, and Sidney's strong presence at the center of the narrative. The family dynamic brings an interesting freshness and helps create a sense of urgency, especially in her relationship with her daughter. The film is entertaining, delivers solid tension sequences, and maintains constant energy.\n\nThe problem emerges in the final stretch. By relying too heavily on nostalgia and false leads, it builds expectations it cannot sustain. The reveal feels weak, with shallow motivations and little emotional impact. In the end, what seemed like a promising return turns into a chapter that entertains along the way but disappoints in its conclusion."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "549eb1e4-27f2-41fb-97c9-cfc2d524e864", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.182401", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "0dc04c67a8caca79773b6429f5d4af78bd1df5a35f82bf56e0367d2fb5cff3ef"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "Grumpyzz", "rating": 5, "date": "2026-02-27", "title": null, "content": "Scream 7 left me pretty mixed overall.\n\nAs a longtime fan who grew up on this franchise, this was easily one of my most anticipated movies of the year. And while there are definite bright spots here, especially the kills with excellent sequences and a few bold swings, it ultimately falls flat in the big finale because of some really questionable narrative decisions.\n\nStarting with the positives: the first act and most of the second is pretty strong. The pacing is quick, the opening scene is honestly a great one, setting the tone for what feels like could've been a dangerous and nuanced iteration of Ghostface. The movie begins exploring themes of toxic nostalgia and AI, which is a smart direction for a seventh entry in a legacy horror franchise and currently very relevant. There's real potential there, but the problem is it never fully came full circle in a compelling manner. Those ideas just fell flat with the third act here, just not getting weaved together very well by the end.\n\nThe real standout here is easily the brutality and kills. The gore is next level here and in my opinion the best in the franchise. There's a kill in the bar sequence that had my entire theater audibly reacting, and I genuinely think it's THE best kill the series has ever done. The tension building in some of the scenes and ideas explored here in these sequences were also a very great addition, adding to the memorability of this film.\n\nSeeing Neve Campbell back in the lead role was also a huge plus, and having Matthew Lillard reprise Stu was a surreal and fun moment for me, coming from someone who wanted him back since Scream (2022). It ties directly into the nostalgia theme -which again, could've landed so much harder if the finale was better.\n\nAbout halfway through, the movie pulls a pretty bold move, something I've always thought would be interesting to see in a Scream film. On paper, it's a fantastic idea and a real swing for the fences. The issue is that it ultimately feels like it exists mainly to justify the third-act twist and to subvert expectations for the sake of it. Great concept but a shaky execution that only exists to justify one of its third act ideas.\n\nAnd that leads to my biggest problem: the third act and reveal.\n\nThe killer reveal, dynamic, and motive are, in my opinion, the weakest in the entire franchise and it's seriously not even close. The entire climax from the reveal to the final fight feels rushed and doesn't give the moment enough time to breathe, with everything happening at break neck speed. Instead of leaving the theater shocked or satisfied, I walked out feeling like it just didn't stick the landing.\n\nThe character work doesn't help either. The arcs feel pretty one dimensional overall, with a lot of retreading rather than evolution. While Scream has never been strictly character study horror, this entry in particular feels narratively thin as it goes on. There are multiple big moments near the end that don't get any compelling resolve, and you can sense the rewrites in the structure when these moments do come.\n\nOverall, Scream 7 isn't a flat out bad movie to me, especially for the seventh entry in a slasher franchise. It has some of the best kills, bold ideas, and a bunch of fun and tension filled moments. I both understand the clear criticisms, and understand the love it's receiving, I'm just sort of in the middle on this one.\n\nI wanted to walk out loving it. Instead, I walked out thinking it was just okay, entertaining but flawed, and ultimately disappointing compared to its potential, hopefully my opinions will change on inevitable rewatch but for now, those are my feelings on Scream 7."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "9cbe686d-98ce-4d00-8846-90ef7e16651c", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.182401", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "f2a7c1996d3b8a6c5dd826f49cf1d0266ca06a4316f0ed41562e0037f7973365"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "drawlife", "rating": 7, "date": "2026-02-25", "title": null, "content": "SCREAM 7 was always going to have a tough job. It had to balance nostalgia with carving out its own identity, and that's a tricky line to walk, especially after all the behind the scenes drama post SCREAM 6. Losing Melissa Barrera and Jenna Ortega was a major shift, so bringing Neve Campbell back wasn't just fan service, it felt necessary. And she absolutely earned that payday.\n\nInitially, I enjoyed SCREAM 5 and 6 upon release. But with some distance and once the initial excitement faded, I realized they didn't stick with me the way I thought they did. For me, SCREAM is Neve Campbell. Maybe that's the millennial in me, but this franchise really does live and die with Sidney Prescott. That's not to discredit 5 and 6, there are some elements to like, but a lot of my attachment came from the thrill of revisiting this world after SCREAM 4.\n\nOn a meta level, SCREAM 7 leans heavily into the nostalgia and retcon era, clearly nodding to the legacy-sequel wave that took off after 2018's HALLOWEEN. The film even comments on how hard it is for franchises to juggle old leads with new blood. You need fresh characters to evolve, but letting go of your defining final girl is easier said than done. Given how strongly I feel that Sidney is the heart of this series, that theme actually resonated with me.\n\nWhen it was announced that Matthew Lillard (Stu), Scott Foley (Roman), and David Arquette (Dewey) would return in some capacity, the movie started to feel like SCREAM ENDGAME. So...did it live up to that hype?\n\nIn some ways, yes. In others, not quite.\n\nThere are moments that genuinely work. The film plays with expectations and builds tension effectively. But the third act is where everything hinges, and that's where I'm split. It doesn't completely stick the landing, but it doesn't derail either. It lands somewhere in the middle.\n\nCourteney Cox has a smaller role this time, but she's reliably strong as always. Mason Gooding and Jasmin Savoy Brown help maintain continuity from the previous films. I was pleasantly surprised by Sidney's daughter, Tatum. She avoids the typical moody-teen stereotype, and Isabel May brings a grounded strength to the role. Her friend group, however, feels more functional than fleshed out, very much there to raise the body count, though the kills themselves are executed well.\n\nThe marketing has been effective, and financially it looks like the film will likely perform well. But I'm unsure about its long-term word of mouth. It doesn't fully satisfy longtime fans, and I'm not convinced it's bold enough to completely win over newcomers either. It plays things a bit safe.\n\nAnd if we're being honest, it's not overly difficult to narrow down who Ghostface might be. The casting makes certain possibilities feel obvious. A few stronger red herrings could have elevated the mystery. Franchise creator Kevin Williamson returns in a writing capacity and steps into the director's chair as well. I was a little hesitant at first, considering he only has one prior directing credit, but outside of a few uneven moments, for the most part he handles it well. He was hired late on the spot for 7 and if there is an 8, and he's involved from the ground up, maybe that's where he could really put his full stamp on it. Also shoutout to Marco Beltrami's score.\n\nIf the box office exceeds expectations and reception skews more positive than negative, a SCREAM 8 feels inevitable. That's just how Hollywood operates. But as a fan, I do think there needs to be an endpoint. Is there room for another story or two? Probably. But how many times can Sidney realistically endure this? At some point, the franchise risks becoming the very thing it once cleverly satirized.\n\nThat \"in-between\" feeling is what defines SCREAM 7. It's somewhat bold, somewhat safe. Nostalgic but restrained. Entertaining, but not definitive. It flirts with meaningful fan service without fully committing, almost as if it's holding one final card for the future.\n\nWhat ultimately anchors everything is Neve Campbell. She brings weight, history, and emotional credibility. She makes it feel like SCREAM.\n\nNothing tops SCREAM 1 and 2 in that order. After that, I'd still place SCREAM 4 third (those motives were ahead of their time and documentary level accurate, even if Emma Roberts and Rory Culkin overpowering everyone remains a stretch). Then I'd slot 7, followed by 5 and 6, and SCREAM 3 at the bottom.\n\nA good entry. Just not the ultimate one.\n\n7/10."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "1f93b1bf-dbb4-43bf-92ec-f5f3b36ed141", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.182401", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "4861c68e3913cb8251f0a514670b07e9cadf6b9aecc157f328f58e876f98a313"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "FeastMode", "rating": 3, "date": "2026-02-27", "title": null, "content": "Scream 5 did something amazing. It executed a requel flawlessly and introduced two new leads that we are fully invested in and want to follow. The characters of Sam and Tara, played by Melissa Barrera and Jenna Ortega, are a huge reason why this beloved franchise returned to prominence.\n\nFor those who don't know, Melissa Barrera spoke out about something that we're not \"allowed\" to criticize. She showed courage we rarely see from celebrities. And Spyglass Studios fired her for it.\n\nJenna Ortega had also publicly spoken out about the same issue in the past. So in solidarity with her on-screen sister, she quit the Scream franchise the next day. Then the directors walked as well. In summary, Spyglass Studios sided with something indefensible and destroyed everything they built with this new set of Scream movies.\n\nEven though I loathed their decision, I figured it was still possible to make something good and rescue the franchise. Difficult, but possible. Anything can be good if done right. So I went in with an open mind, hoping for another great entry in a movie series I love...\n\nBut Scream 7 is terrible. I could feel it pretty early. It's like a pale shadow or imitation. I kept trying to be patient and give it a chance. But I just wasn't invested. At all.\n\nPart of the problem is that we need to be introduced to a new cast with a new main final girl. And that final girl is so lame. I don't think it's the actress's fault. The character is horribly written and difficult to root for. She can't hold a candle to Sydney or Sam/Tara.\n\nThe movie is more predictable than any prior entry. It's also filled with stupidity, to the point of me rolling my eyes more than once.\n\nIn general, everything that makes the Scream movies awesome is inferior in part 7. The firing of Barrera has to be one of the most bafflingly moronic studio decisions I've witnessed in my 40 years of movie fandom.\n\n(1 viewing, opening Thursday UltraScreen 2/26/2026)"}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "86326746-b633-46d2-9383-860bf941cdb2", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.182401", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "7d69ed3530dfa4cd339f1d05088cf114e41d341986bdc7c1b94e05f0aa777968"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "Sleepin_Dragon", "rating": 6, "date": "2026-03-02", "title": null, "content": "Sidney Prescott is now living a quiet life in Indiana with her husband and daughter, Tatum. However, history inevitably repeats itself when a new Ghostface emerges and commences a fresh killing spree. With the past refused to stay buried, Gale Weathers is once again on hand to help Sidney navigate the familiar terror.\n\nBringing back director Kevin Williamson was a smart move; the film possesses significantly more DNA from the original run than the last couple of entries. It successfully recaptures that particular 90s slasher vibe, aided by costumes and sets that feel authentic to the franchise's roots rather than a modern imitation. However, perhaps times have changed, or the format has simply been done to death since the first movie's epic arrival. It plays more like a straight-up slasher, missing much of the sharp wit and dark humour that once defined the series.\n\nThe highlight is undoubtedly the opening. The sequences in the \"murder house\" took me right back to 1996, packing in a genuine sense of atmosphere that the rest of the film struggles to maintain. While the music is used to great effect-with certain tracks deliberately tugging at the heartstrings of long-term fans-the ending is likely to leave many viewers disappointed. We all knew AI would eventually feature in the plot, and while its inclusion doesn't disappoint, it does feel like a sign of the times.\n\nNeve Campbell continues to shine as the definitive \"final girl.\" Time has been incredibly kind to her, and she remains the undisputed soul of the franchise. There is, quite literally, nothing new on display here, but for fans of the original, there is enough to satisfy. Between the heavy use of the nostalgia hand, the references to the past, and a familiar face or two, it's a perfectly watchable experience. It simply serves as another reminder of the current lack of imagination in Hollywood.\n\n6/10."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "b9a1c7ac-41f7-4d9f-a04b-2d11fa209976", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.182401", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "1b76fbd73e087307e0c4f05dcfc96678af7adc89e9a5845e6a894c8fa501ea53"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "johnnyhbtvs27", "rating": 3, "date": "2026-02-26", "title": null, "content": "Seen the reviews and ratings for Scream 7 and thought it was because of all the people intentionally giving it poor ratings due to the boycott. Nope, turns out it is just a terrible movie and a stain on the franchise.\n\nThe levels of stupidity this film reaches needs to be studied. The new cast are terrible, the old aren't much better and the killer reveals.....oh dear.\n\nMight start taking pilates."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "63a47577-02f2-422a-89c6-a0e4011d567b", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.182401", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "3c05c0b1639b89365add39c6fba5eec366f723b8d1898ec32d9b2b4f5608c0bf"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "isaacsundaralingam", "rating": 3, "date": "2026-03-01", "title": null, "content": "Seven movies into the franchise, and we finally get a Scream installment that's actually trash. Maybe this was the blood splatter on the wall all along - I mean, it is a horror franchise, after all, so a catastrophic entry was statistically inevitable. Still, that doesn't make it any less disappointing. For a series that has managed to stay surprisingly consistent over the years, this is the first time it genuinely feels like it has lost its identity.\n\nWhat Scream has always had in its favor is the luxury of not taking itself too seriously. The films thrived on sharp meta-humor; winking at the audience, poking fun at horror tropes, and occasionally even mocking their own legacy. They weren't comedies, but the genre-savvy satire was the trademark. Here, though, that clever self-awareness is traded in for lazy writing. The film constantly reminds us that we're in the metaphorical seventh installment and that this chapter is about \"nostalgia bait\", smugly acknowledging the trope before proceeding to indulge in it shamelessly. It's meta without wit, and commentary without insight.\n\nThe characters are easily the worst in the franchise: hollow, one-note canon fodder designed purely to be killed. The action is mostly lackluster (save for one genuinely creative kill), and nearly every sequence hinges on characters making aggressively stupid decisions. But the biggest failure is the reveal. In a Scream movie, the unmasking of Ghostface is the payoff - and here it's random, pointless, and painfully obvious. The motivation is paper-thin, the red herrings are nonexistent, and midway through, a character appears whose existence only makes sense if they're one of the killers. It's a disastrous reveal that drags an already bad film even lower. Ultimately, this feels less like a misstep and more like the beginning of the end for the franchise."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "6ac88a7c-6f42-42d1-9d1f-caef2985bab2", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.182401", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "e117b74607b8bcc8d2d16b684fb6cb65ca16e5baead99a91048ccb9f905ef84b"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "williard2194", "rating": 3, "date": "2026-02-27", "title": null, "content": "Scream 7 is a nostalgia-fest with a forced subplot regarding the dynamic between Sidney and her daughter, but that's not why we watch Scream movies anyway. The heart of this franchise has always been the murder mystery dynamic and trying to figure out who the killer(s) are, and then being blown away by the reveal at the end. Well, this movie simply ruins that.\n\nThe entire Ghostface storyline for this film is based around the possibility of Stu being alive. However, the revealed killers have quite literally NOTHING to do with Stu in the slightest. As a matter of fact, their motives are just dumb and Jessica's explanation doesn't help that. I legitimately can't even remember the male's name (if we were even told it in the movie). It felt like the writers made them the killers just so they could say it was someone the audience didn't see coming. However, they insulted the audience's intelligence in doing so.\n\nMatthew Lillard's performance steals the show, and Neve Campbell does a great job as well. However, this franchise truly has nothing but nostalgia to offer anymore, and Scream 7 overwhelmingly proves that."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "fbd3008d-42a9-48ef-b9d4-2cf1f2e3d3cd", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.182401", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "923831b33ed508601e5050da11e9c34600babf00c5ac7b5151b88c8f1ea83429"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "jp_91", "rating": 6, "date": "2026-02-26", "title": null, "content": "\"Scream 7\" is a fairly average film. The beginning is somewhat weak, and the story is full of scenes paying homage to the first two films and references to parts 3, 4, 5, and 6, all aimed at appealing to nostalgia. This is how Kevin Williamson crafted a script that fluctuates between highs and lows. At times it's very slow, at others it's bland, but it also has a couple of good murder scenes, Gale Weathers' first appearance on screen in this seventh installment is memorable, and during Act 3 a final revelation that showcases the most insipid and boring killers in the entire saga. Tatum Evans's introduction isn't particularly interesting; the character is written in a clich\u00e9d and very boring way. If Williamson broke the rules of the slasher subgenre in 1996 and revitalized it, this time his style becomes completely clich\u00e9d. Kevin Williamson as director is very clueless, although a couple of scenes have good suspense, perhaps a stroke of luck or a fleeting inspiration from having worked with the master Wes Craven. Neve Campbell delivers a solid performance as Sidney Prescott-Evans, and while her return is celebrated, her affection for the character is lacking, for over a decade, she's made it clear that the \"Scream\" franchise isn't her top priority, and money is a convenient excuse for her return (which is perfectly within her rights) demonstrating resentment towards the saga since the public only remembers her for her character. Courteney Cox gives a ferocious and incredible performance as the ever-fierce Gale Weathers, demonstrating genuine affection for her character, and breaking the rules of the final girl stereotype, a true scream queen. Jasmin Savoy Brown returns as Mindy Meeks, delivering a somewhat irritating performance, while Mason Gooding, as her twin brother Chad Meeks, is decent but nothing special. Isabel May, on the other hand, comes across as very inexperienced as a survivor, not having what it takes to be a worthy final girl. The appearances of Mckenna Grace and Celeste O'Connor are wasted on characters that could have been better written. The rest of the cast delivers a range of performances: good, average, and bad. The cinematography is forgettable and at times resembles that of a low-quality television series. The deaths are gory, but only a couple are well done. The music also evokes nostalgia, featuring the most iconic themes from the saga. It's worth noting the absence of Melissa Barrera (unfairly fired) and Jenna Ortega as sisters Samantha and Tara Carpenter, respectively, and who have become iconic for their on-screen chemistry in parts 5 and 6. It is necessary to mention that Melissa Barrera as Sam achieved a memorable performance as a very tough final girl with killer genes who is hard to kill (something that Tatum Evans' character lacks). \"Scream 7\" is a simple and predictable film. This installment is totally inferior to the rest of the films in the saga."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "27118aa7-3906-4475-85f8-16e1dfe9b1ff", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.182401", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "05467f75744a19f37607d98d1d4a33ff2ca0ff56a342bca057c4df5e26c3d56f"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "jared-25331", "rating": 1, "date": "2026-02-27", "title": null, "content": "Scream 7 (2026) is the seventh entry in the Scream movie franchise that was written and directed by Kevin Williamson and it follows Sidney Prescott and her daughter, Tatum, being targeted by a new Ghostface killer. This movie has gone through a lot of controversy that left a bad taste in my mouth leading up to the release date, but I wanted to give the movie a chance because I love this franchise and every movie including the television series have been consistently great. Unfortunately, this movie was absolutely freaking atrocious and it was everything I didn't want to see in this franchise.\n\nPositives for Scream 7 (2026): The best thing in this movie is the mother-daughter dynamic between Sidney and Tatum Prescott as well as the performances from Neve Campbell and Isabel May. There are some great kills that are very gory. That's all I've got to say for the positives.\n\nNegatives for Scream 7 (2026): This movie is to the Scream franchise what The Rise of Skywalker (2019) was to Star Wars. This movie was clearly being used to nostalgia bait the fans to thinking it's a good movie when it really has no idea what it wants to be. The opening scene is awful and the people who are brutally murdered have nothing to do with the rest of the movie. You have characters like Gale, Mindy and Chad, who show up for a while and they disappear for a while with no explanation for their absence. The twins don't even act like the same characters from the previous movies. The movie references the events from Scream VI (2023) in a way that was annoying while making comments I found to be disrespectful and I felt personally attacked by them. There are horror sequences that look cool at first, but they make no sense with the events leading up to them. The movie tries to trick you into believing that Stu Macher is alive because everyone says, \"We never saw Stu die\" except we did see him die and those people are freaking idiots for even believing it. The killer reveal was awful and it was spoiled for me, but I didn't even care at that point and it was so obvious who it was. The motivation for the killer was atrocious which makes no sense at all and you can't tell me I'm wrong. And finally, I felt nothing while I was watching the movie until it ended and I was filled with so much anger and rage.\n\nOverall, Scream 7 (2026) is a massive dumpster fire that disrespected me as a fan of this franchise and it is the movie from 2026 so far that I hate the most with a passion."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "0e9e1dbe-6363-4db8-aba3-5f002730bfd2", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.182401", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "fa4936d32b27fa94ce19721c2a8de4e95380d5864e15cc0344ff50a75e6332bc"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "BA_Harrison", "rating": 3, "date": "2026-02-27", "title": null, "content": "It's the only explanation I can think of for how easily Ghostface's knife goes through the first victim's skull in Scream 7.\n\nI'm a big fan of the first two Scream films -- to me, they are a perfect double bill: the original film breathed new life into the tired slasher genre, with it's hip meta approach, and the second movie expanded on this further, introducing the rules of the horror sequel, a great idea perfectly executed. It should have stopped there.\n\nScreams three through five were unnecessary money makers that did little but rehash what had gone before. Scream VI was marginally better, largely thanks to stars Melissa Barrera and Jenna Ortega, so when Scream 7 was initially announced, I actually had a glimmer of hope for the film. But then all of that political stuff happened, which saw Barrera and Ortega leaving the project, followed by the film's director, with Scream scribe Kevin Williamson rewriting the script and taking over directorial duties.\n\nAnd so we get this... a clumsily thrown together mess that tries to make up for the awkward absence of the previous instalment's stars by heaping on the fan service, but with little style, finesse or originality. I won't bother to explain the asinine plot, suffice to say that Sidney Prescott once again finds herself (and her loved ones) targeted by yet another Ghostface (or three), and there's an embarrassingly bad attempt at shoehorning that hot topic -- A. I. -- into the storyline.\n\nNow I'd be lying if I said that the film was totally worthless. There are a couple of decent moments, most of which were given away in the trailer. One death scene that happens fairly early on is truly nasty and very gory, and if that had set the tone for the rest of the film, I probably would have left the cinema happy. But sadly this isn't the case. There's one other kill involving a ridiculously pointy beer pump that make me chuckle, and a tense scene that sees Ghostface attempting to stab Sidney and her daughter Tatum (played by Isabel May, who looks like young Jennifer Lawrence, which isn't a bad thing) through a dry wall, but that's about it for the good stuff. The rest of the film is the usual mundane stabbing and running we've seen many times before.\n\nUnfortunately, there's plenty of bad to talk about...\n\nFirstly, what the hell has Courtney Cox done to herself? I found her 'new' face extremely distracting. But she's not nearly as hard to watch as Matthew Lillard, who is only on the screen for a few minutes, but who makes every second count by being as ridiculously over the top as possible; if it was me, I'd be embarrassed to take the cheque for that performance. To be honest, the acting is pretty dreadful throughout, but then they are working from a horrible script - has Williamson forgotten how to write altogether?\n\nThe aforementioned A. I. nonsense is a desperate attempt at addressing today's issues, but it will age like milk; the scene in which Tatum's boyfriend shows he has been experimenting with deep fakes already looks awful. And possibly the worst thing about the film is the Scooby Doo reveal at the end, in which the Ghostfaces are revealed to be secondary characters with the lamest motives ever. It's pure trash.\n\nOverall, Scream 7 is just another lame sequel that does nothing new. Time to call it a day, I think.\n\nMy rating is 3/10."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "e8e42703-a0d8-43c3-af5b-027308aa8556", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.182401", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "018fa83feeda806663f443eb6da66d4dab7da2a39e70415cb3fbaa6250161bc1"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "leestoych", "rating": 5, "date": "2026-02-26", "title": null, "content": "Scream 7 was doomed from the beginning, regardless of its final product. Losing the natural story progression of Tara and Sam was a massive blow. The prior two films, Scream and Scream VI, laid some interesting foundations that this installment could have expanded on in meaningful ways.\n\nInstead, Scream 7 had to essentially reinvent the wheel, and that proved to be far too difficult. Rather than building on what was already working, the film feels like it is scrambling to reset itself.\n\nWithout diving into specifics, it comes across as trying too hard with very little payoff. The story and characters feel lacklustre, and the core basics that made the previous installments so effective, tension, sharp meta commentary, and genuine emotional stakes, feel noticeably absent here.\n\nThat said, Ghostface being Ghostface is always awesome to watch."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "1dce314c-16ee-493c-a09a-db1195185be6", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.182401", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "0e24c83862effdbe1c060b865e2e70f935930f69b6d1f9f66bfa7c9b7e23a957"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "LetsReviewThat26", "rating": 7, "date": "2026-03-05", "title": null, "content": "With Neve Campbell back as sidney prescott scream 7 contines on the beloved franchise. There is a lot to love about this movie. The atmosphere created and the soundtrack work well.theres a really great mix of cast also including joel mchall as sidneys husband mark and daughter tatum played by isabel may. They also managed to have a sense of humor amoungst the horror and its just a really fun continuation that manages to be more gory and twisty then you would expect."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "ec945d0c-ecb8-44d2-ae03-89638f115942", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.182401", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "2b114d752d6eeb18426c87d9df7ca879da1a787db60a790e8029a05d7993fac6"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "Simoncito2025", "rating": 8, "date": "2026-02-25", "title": null, "content": "I went in with high hopes, only watched half of the trailer because I didn't want any spoilers.\n\nI have to say I was not disappointed. Thanks to Kevin Williams returning and Sydney being the main character again, we got the old feeling back.\n\nThey used several scenes including soundtrack that were almost replicas of the first part. A lot of references to the O. G. movie trilogy. It was so well executed.\n\nThe Killer reveal was okay-ish. But I enjoyed it.\n\nThis will definitely be one of my 2026 favorites. They did well. Great cast. Great writing. Great direction. Great Cinematography.\n\nI don't think another part is needed. But I would watch it if the team and cast stayed the same."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "25ce6bd5-2db2-4a33-8a94-c54e76f54f81", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.182401", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "23713610f88f39df0e6aa67f85e53be7d1b1af39d94ab97a2337dce21088fb98"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "MFC9", "rating": 7, "date": "2026-02-27", "title": null, "content": "Yes indeed everyone's favourite final girl is back after her Scream 6 hiatus, and it is so good to see her again. Don't listen to the negative reviews, Neve never disappoints, with this latest instalment another winner.\n\nSidney is happily married in another small town far away from Woodsboro with her teen daughter mirroring her own teen years, complete with creepy looking boyfriend Billy Loomis-ing his way through her bedroom window.\n\nAnother Ghostface is inexplicably gutting teens and burning OG houses down, with Sidney and her daughter in the crosshairs. Probably Campbell's best performance, with Courtney Cox again making us forget all about Monica Geller as Team Gail returns in awesome fashion. Loved it 7/10."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "0661fea1-4c2d-4378-93c0-dc872b9f5919", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.182401", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "94706506b898aa86779f87946ffc06180bca759436f15f67265b2f45e19b930c"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "ethanbresnett", "rating": 5, "date": "2026-03-07", "title": null, "content": "I was really looking for reasons to love this film as I'm such a fan of the Scream franchise. Unfortunately, it is far and away the weakest of all of them and an entirely forgettable entry.\n\nThe story wasn't awful, and actually showed some promise. It was good to see Sydney back as she is such an iconic character, and her having a family was an interesting dynamic. Isabel May as her daughter Tatum was solid, but deserved a better written role. In fact, the whole mother daughter relationship could have been much better. There were some good Ghostface sequences and the slasher gore was top notch. I also really enjoyed the opening sequence, which was the high of the film and was top notch Scream work.\n\nHowever, so many of the story elements felt so lazy. The Ghostface reveal itself was boring and unsatisfying and didn't even really make sense. The roles of Gale and Chad and Mindy were pointless and added little to proceedings. The writing was so cliche and tired for the most part. For example, does anybody know a 17 year old who has their phone on loud? Come on writers of Hollywood, find better ways to move your story along than having a teenager have their phone ringing loudly. It's just lazy.\n\nA real shame, as having Sydney Prescott back at the helm should have been a slam dunk for this franchise, but they somehow managed to fumble it. There are a few highs in this film worth checking out, and fans of the franchise will need to watch it for continuity sake, but movie goer casuals might want to give it a miss."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "f85fb046-fce7-4aa3-8751-e56857e40c8d", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.182401", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "a83949df865de7db1112a005a0aed78d21004bf0f432425518e20ef89c2bbc45"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "MovimanBond", "rating": 2, "date": "2026-02-27", "title": null, "content": "As a slasher fan, I went to the theater with hope - and, unfortunately, walked out feeling like I had wasted my evening.\n\nHonestly, there was more suspense in a bowling alley.\n\nSo what's the problem with the film?\n\nIts astonishing banality and emotional emptiness. The characters feel like cardboard cutouts, existing purely to fill space - there's no inner life, no depth. You don't believe in them, and, more importantly, you don't care about them. When someone gets killed, it barely registers - and that's a fatal flaw for a slasher.\n\nThe dramaturgy falls apart: the midpoint drags so badly you start checking your watch. The staging feels like a first-year film school exercise - technically everything is there, but something essential is missing. The direction adds nothing new to the franchise's mythology, no fresh visual language or creative perspective. The plot is predictable, the conflicts merely exist without development, and the attempts to play on nostalgia feel more like exploitation of legacy than an evolution of it.\n\nThis is yet another reminder that some stories deserve to end at the right time.\n\nIf you truly want to experience the spirit of the franchise, it's better to revisit the earlier entries - from the original Scream through the fifth installment - or watch the Scream TV series with Willa Fitzgerald, where the tension and dramatic structure feel far more alive.\n\nNot recommended."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "8e7aa1eb-b107-44d0-972c-5b4f1273a2bb", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.182401", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "674bb1728a0de49217b985fb64b0c3b74d18b3674db43fbe626be05cb3fa592c"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "fabiolpinheiro1993", "rating": 7, "date": "2026-02-26", "title": null, "content": "Scream 7 may not bring much that's truly new to the franchise, and that in itself feels like a wasted opportunity - especially with the return of Neve Campbell after she skipped the sixth installment due to a pay dispute. This should have been a groundbreaking entry, both narratively and visually.\n\nThat said, it's still incredibly entertaining and fun to watch. I can't help but always have a great time with this franchise, and this installment is no exception.\n\nFiguring out who the killer is this time comes with a fun new twist that taps into a very current theme. It's genuinely intriguing, especially considering the high body count. However, while the mystery itself is strong, the revelation doesn't quite live up to it. The new killers aren't given enough depth to feel fully fleshed out, and their motivations don't feel as justified or impactful as they could have been.\n\nThe film remains self-aware, as always, though a few creative decisions could have been handled better. Sidney's daughter, introduced as a new character, isn't particularly memorable, and I'm not entirely sold on the casting choice for the role.\n\nUltimately, the main strength of the film lies in the nostalgia of having the original characters back together. It's nearly impossible to top both the legacy characters and the actresses portraying them - their presence alone elevates the experience.\n\nThere's plenty of action and a generous number of kills to satisfy any slasher fan. And with the eighth installment already in the works, I'm excited to see where the franchise goes next."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "2cad466c-980e-4f4f-836e-6173425f9d53", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.182401", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "ff180e3b0529cfebed69f4c467424cc5ea357404f5df048646add9d1ed9f72c0"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "bbevis-47954", "rating": 3, "date": "2026-03-01", "title": null, "content": "Scream 7 Is a rushed complete waste of time. Its not suspenseful, scary, thrilling or contains any good set pieces the last two movies in the franchise had. There is no character development for Sydney, so Neve Campbell's deserved 7 million payday was for nothing. The only reason Scream 7 gets a few points if because 3 of the kills were solid. The rest were stupid characters you didjt care about being killed off in boring ways.\n\nThe killer reveal is by far the worst in the whole franchise. The motivation to kill is absolutely ridiculous.\n\nI regret spending money on this movie."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "92454135-7f20-4376-a1e2-58026beefe1d", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.182401", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "b822634d4f7caa87e174dc99c266356b0a02b70bf1a1a8431dd67c8b1ef4b559"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "HabibieHakim123", "rating": 3, "date": "2026-02-25", "title": null, "content": "The attempt to keep this franchise going without the newer returning characters is painfully obvious throughout the film, they were the ones who gave the series new life, especially in the last two entries, for me, Scream VI still stands out surprisingly as the best in the franchise, it struck a strong balance between legacy characters and the newer generation, and that combination worked quite well in my opinion based on the last two previous movie.\n\nNow with Scream 7, the absence of Melissa Barrera and Jenna Ortega is impossible to ignore, without them, the film feels less like a natural continuation and more like a forced cash grab, worse than that, it feels insulting to the franchise, both the plot and concept is stupid and barely makes sense, the execution is horrible, the pacing is boring, the tension is nowhere to be found, this is supposed to be a Scream movie, and yet there's no real suspense.\n\nNeve Campbell is the only one who seems like she's actually trying, everyone else feels like they showed up, said their lines, and went home with a paycheck, and Stu? A fan-favorite psychopath, completely mishandled, instead of doing something bold or interesting, they did him dirty, there's no way most Stu and Scream fans are okay with this treatment, it's careless and honestly disrespectful.\n\nThe killer reveal is horrible, the motive is even worse, the explanation makes it all collapse, by the end, i didn't even care anymore, the only reason i rank this slightly above Scream 4 is because it looks and directed way better than whatever Wes Craven did with the 4th one back in 2011, again, insulting.\n\nI'm not even a die-hard fan of this franchise, but this is one of the most obviously forced sequels i've seen in years, unless Melissa Barrera and Jenna Ortega come back, i'm not showing up for Scream 8."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "334adb24-a9f9-4ef2-a881-6acf0a50a365", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.182401", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "c98fd4fd9acba9f21725c02e0f3aa0512b7ff5e8e3b73a2a6d21a19eb850aad9"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "DylanP-8264", "rating": 9, "date": "2026-02-28", "title": null, "content": "Scream 7 was an amazing experience. I had the enjoyable experience to be able to see this in a packed XD theater. It was packed with tons of scream super fans and gear. Clapping and cheering at different scenes is what makes seeing a movie with tons of people in a theater so special. And a big franchise like Scream is what makes it even more awesome. But now let's talk about the actual movie itself.\n\nScream 7 is set in Pine Grove, Indiana. This is the new home of Sidney Prescott and her daughter Tatum. Ghostface has come to Pine Grove to end Sidney once and for all.\n\nThe opening scene is one of the most important parts of a Scream movie. This one does a great job of setting the tone of this movie. It was really interesting to see how the Macher house had become this museum of all past killings in the franchise. This was certainly a call back to many of the movies that came before. The brutality and overall shock factor of this opening scene was something that I did not expect. Little did I know these were the tamest kills in the entire movie.\n\nFor me, I felt like this movie had a different tone than its predecessors. This movie was more intense and suspenseful with less comedic relief. I'm not complaining about this at all, it's just cool to see them writing something different instead of the same formula over and over again. On that same tone, the use of ai in this movie was really cool to show how long these movie have been here for.\n\nThe acting in this movie was on another level. Of course, the Scream Queen, Neve Campbell, was incredible. Courtney Cox brings the fire to the screen as Gale Weathers. The new casting of Isabel May was a great decision. She does a phenomenal job playing Sidney's daughter.\n\nNow for Ghostface and the kills. I won't spoil who ghostface is, but I will say I was completely wrong. The kills in this movie are really what separates this one from the rest. It really takes modern horror to another level. Ghostface is an absolute beast in this movie stopping at nothing for Sidney and his daughter. I felt like the ghostface mask had a nice update in this installment and it was very well done. Props to the costume crew.\n\nThis all couldn't have been done though without the return of Kevin Williamson. He actually directed this movie along with writing it of course. He cooked up a great movie!\n\nThis was such a fun movie with so many intense and awesome scenes that will be very memorable! Can't wait to rewatch it when it comes out on streaming!"}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "e63b26a3-0561-4327-b263-a7ab61c3925a", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.182401", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "0214753a8ee9b130d9753160c5791a941a65b945cbb9b73423b0b15b9782b72c"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "Hellraiser-Carlin", "rating": 3, "date": "2026-03-01", "title": null, "content": "I have been a fan of these movies since the first one came out 20 years or so ago. And I am more than happy knowing it's a complete cash grab, The story still needs to have a slight element of believability and campiness but this one fell well short of the mark!\n\nThe killers are so far removed from the main cast you really have to squint your brain to remember that one scene that one guy was in for 9 seconds!\n\nMake another I'll watch it, but try harder next time you lazy lot!"}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "5aaa7c42-c98b-43fb-a60f-799e3b141e31", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.182401", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "11dacc565c38b4e673d6aab80a334d84b50a7f26e6403f0f12c5e1c9e5924aed"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "greyKbarclay", "rating": 7, "date": "2026-02-27", "title": null, "content": "Neve Campbell brings the house down, showing the world just why she has managed to do what no other Scream Queen has done in sustaining a franchise for 30 years! Electrifyingly powerful. And Isabel May stuns as Tatum Evans, her big chase through the desolate streets of Pine Grove, seeing her truly innocent boyfriend get brutally stabbed before her own violent capture in her own mother's cafe. Magnetic, truly.\n\nI do feel that the teenage characters were underutilised. While both sets of kills at the theatre and tavern were tense and chaotic and beautiful all in the same breath, I just don't think that they had enough enlightenment to create the same unique dynamic that we saw in Scream. Lucas was the only character that had more shading to him, his self-proclaimed true crime obsession putting him straight in the sights of Mindy Meeks as a Ghostface killer. I think that a better way of introducing this new barrage of youthful characters would've been a party, in true Scream fashion. McKenna Grace simply should've had more scenes but that shot of her dangling from her wires, cooly backlit with harsh spotlight and her entrails dangling viscerally. Superb, I think Wes Craven would've been proud.\n\nI'll need to rewatch this film just to narrow down my concrete feelings about it, but at this current point in time I believe that this killer's motive to be an inversion of Scream 4. It would make sense considering Williamson's perchance for typical genre inversion, and that Scream 4 was the last time that he was involved in a Scream film. While I might have felt a little off, Jessica literally had nothing to do with Sidney (at face value) but once you begin to unpack her motive you begin to realise that all that personal connection that is typically seen with a Ghostface killer is all on Jessica's side. She has been living this parasocial, idolatrous relationship with Sidney for well over ten years now, and feels deep betrayal at her disappearance from the public eye and her absence during the New York spree (which wouldn't of made sense for Sidney to have been involved with; that wasn't her story).\n\nI do think that with all the AI involvement, they should've leaned more into it, it would've given the franchise an interesting commentary to discuss. It has been employed is a useful way, Williamson once again pushing forward character development; Sidney can no longer be shaken by cryptic words down the phone, no, the only thing that will shake her is an intense flash from the past.\n\nOverall, I have found this film to be a good, classic Scream fun, and once again gives the audience something new to go away and ponder. In my opinion, the third act reveal was weak in comparison to the rest of the film, and indeed the rest of the franchise, but it is still a worthwhile watch, with punchy comedic dialogue, taut pacing and the astounding cinematography."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "e570fa7c-faed-44ad-aec8-31e02b3f5250", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.182401", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "8295039fa0ad7bec361ef86cdc5a91a760a8c366f375b368697a622dc20f16f4"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "jtindahouse", "rating": 10, "date": "2026-02-26", "title": null, "content": "10/10 might seem like an over the top score for a film that I found a few flaws in. Here's the thing though, if I have as much fun in the cinema as I did with this film, to give it anything less than a 10 would be wrong. This film was a blast, flaws be damned.\n\nThe opening scene of any 'Scream' movie is very important. It sets the tone and gets you back into the swing of things. I liked the opening scene of 'Scream 7' a lot. The nostalgic throwbacks to events from the original, and the phone call with the \"play along at home\" trivia questions, all nice touches.\n\nFrom there we go into quite a lengthy period without much action while all the characters are set up. This probably couldn't been cut down a bit, it did drag a little.\n\nOnce the killings begin though the pacing picks right back up and doesn't relent at all from there on out. There are some absolutely brutal kills in this movie. It wasn't afraid to get gory.\n\nThe ending was a bit of a letdown I will say. Probably the worst finish a 'Scream' movie has had so far. It just didn't quite feel worthy of a franchise that has always finished its films in such epic ways.\n\nStill, as I mentioned I had an absolute blast with this movie and it's unlikely I'll have a better time in the cinema in 2026 than I did with this film. Bring on 'Scream 8'! 10/10."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "f86fc5ef-c283-49bc-a08b-273b6a9dbbc1", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.182401", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "e1b9cd293ccfb643d468a19f9b03fa93090728b3b831a0ab2a765f03d0e82e6e"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "Mightymax15801", "rating": 2, "date": "2026-02-27", "title": null, "content": "Where do I start with this catastrophe? I'll start with by saying the things I liked about it which isn't much first the kills were actually pretty good. That's pretty much it. Now the bad part which is 90% of this film. First why the hell do we introduce 2 new main protagonist just for them not to be in the third film of this new trilogy but keep the 2 side characters make that make sense. Next why was Stu a deep fake the most disappointing thing about this movie. Stu was hyped up so much just for him to be a stupid deep fake. Now and days it feels like every movie needs to have AI and some sort which is just extremely annoying. And the two ghost faces, I can't remember their name they're so unmemorable and not even in the movie for 99% of the damn movie. And the plot armor for these movies the husband lives after getting stabbed at least 10 times and bleeding out for hours at least but he still lives. And there are some things that I didn't like this about this movie, but I'm not gonna get into it cause it's not worth my time. But a positive not not even about the move but the souvenir, popcorn, bucket, and cup were pretty cool. Overall this movie sucks and just a disgrace to scream franchise."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "198d73df-6dcc-4c6b-ad41-a8dd30437dd0", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.182401", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "d3fc9506c6dcc29809c7b14ea3b4f7a4837e130a0f6ecb9e86ee09cafc526ddb"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "andreagcumunel", "rating": 2, "date": "2026-02-28", "title": null, "content": "I don't think this film really delivered for any of the already divided groups in the fanbase. It somehow managed to frustrate nearly all of them at once.\n\nFirst, the fans of Melissa Barrera and her character arc. Even if bringing her back wasn't possible, there were still multiple ways to respect the role she played in the previous films. Instead, the movie signals that her storyline ultimately didn't matter and that everything still revolves around Sidney Prescott. For viewers who were invested in the newer arc, it feels like the film quietly erases it. That alone alienates a significant part of the audience.\n\nSecond, the longtime fans who think Stu Macher could still be alive. The film had two clear options: bring him back properly, or definitively confirm he died in the original movie. Instead, the marketing leaned heavily into the \"maybe he's alive\" angle for months. What the movie actually delivers is a strange middle ground, a deepfake cameo that doesn't really justify itself, doesn't explain why it exists, and still avoids confirming anything clearly. After all that buildup, those fans are left exactly where they started.\n\nThird, the viewers who never believed the Stu theory and just wanted a fresh Ghostface reveal with a strong motive. That didn't really land either. The reveal is arguably one of the weakest in the franchise, and the explanation is oddly convoluted. Ironically, people argued that bringing Stu back would be \"too confusing,\" yet the villain monologue here ends up far messier than a straightforward resurrection plot would have been. At one point it almost feels like Sidney should have stopped her mid monologue and said, \"Wait... what?\"\n\nSo the result is unusual: Barrera fans feel dismissed, Stu theorists feel baited, and viewers who simply wanted a new direction didn't get a satisfying payoff either. That's a difficult balance to miss across the board. The frustrating part is that it wasn't impossible to satisfy these groups. Acknowledging the legacy of Sam Carpenter and Tara Carpenter while introducing new characters, delivering a strong Ghostface reveal, and committing to a bold twist, potentially even bringing Stu back in a meaningful way, could have tied the old and new eras together instead of leaving everyone unsatisfied."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "30a251bb-9eb5-40b5-a0d2-fcadd7b04663", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.182401", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "82cdfc9240a8439cbddb705fba53104cd825ab1e2d98fbbf7d3beb59d6aef234"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "BretM-3", "rating": 7, "date": "2026-03-03", "title": null, "content": "I went into this movie as unbiased as can be, and (even though this might be a controversial opinion) I really enjoyed it! I thought the relationship the movie built between Sidney and Tatum was really good, and that all the other characters were good as well. Unlike most, I really enjoyed Gale's role in the movie and I enjoyed that she had Chad and Mindy with her as a way to naturally bring them back and to tie this movie to the past 2. In addition, Sidney's husband, Mark, did more than I thought he would and I was surprised he actually made it out of the movie alive! I also really enjoyed how they worked Matthew Lillard and all the deceased Legacy characters in. So even though Stu is still dead, it was fun to have Matthew Lillard play him again though the AI deepfakes. I also thought the cinematography was good in this movie. A lot of people have hated on it, but I thought the movie looked just as good as the last 2. And man, the kills in this movie were awesome! More gnarly and brutal kills like what we saw in the past 2. The one everyone's talking about is the \"beer kill\" which was really cool! Now, the big elephant in the room when talking about this movie is The Ghostface(s). Well, I didn't really have a problem with the killers themselves, but I thought the motives were stupid! The single worst part of this movie is her motive. Not only was it stupidly complicated, but it doesn't really make a whole lot of sense. I guess you could just say she's crazy, (which is true) but it feels like the motive was an afterthought once they figured out the first half of the movie. But overall, I did really enjoy the film. Its biggest flaw isn't necessarily the killers themselves, but mainly it's their motives. Other than that, I felt like the characters were well acted and written, the kill scenes were amazing, and the cinematography looked great too. So definitely give this movie a try and don't listen to all the haters!"}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "0d51462c-aead-4bd9-80a5-f510d8729fdf", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.182401", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "421668d23e61de34637d99a6a44b3247abfc4be666e61ff687e277ad52b90684"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "vengeance20", "rating": 7, "date": "2026-02-28", "title": null, "content": "So, with the last 2 entries of the Scream Franchise proving to be disappointments, 5 especially being the worst one in my opinion! I wasn't holding out much hope for this one, however, the trailers intrigued me enough & of course, you have to go & see it at least once...!\n\nWhen a new Ghostface killer emerges in the town where Sidney Prescott has built a new life, her darkest fears are realised as her daughter becomes the next target!\n\nI found the film to be pretty good & a vast improvement over Screams 5 & 6 easily! I was on the fence as to whether I wanted to like this one or not, but I did, surprisingly enough! The plot, twist & killers motives might not be great or much, but hey, compared to the last 2 entries, anything is better even if it's half arsed & average!\n\nThe opening is pretty good with the Stu Macher House Museum! I liked that & the other references, call backs & Easter eggs to the previous films in the Franchise! The kills are pretty gruesome & gory, so there's no disappointment there, that & there's some eye candy with the women! The humour was good too!\n\nThe films runtime is 1 hour & 47 minutes (107 minutes) & has some decent pacing to go with it! The killer reveal was surprising, but weak in a sense like the plot which seemed half baked to be honest! It was great to see the original cast come back even though they were AI deep fakes! The cast in general all done well with their parts!\n\nOverall, it's kind of refreshing that we get a good Scream sequel for once & ironically enough, one which seems to be hated by critics, rolls eyes but hey, what are you going to do!? This one was a vast improvement over Scream 5 & 6 & one you should definitely check out in Cinemas! It may not be amazing, but hey, it's pretty great stuff!\n\n7/10."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "6d990d35-1981-4e4d-b44f-2003ac6cbd67", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184413", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "4d42e9a5e9386ddbe0b97212a83f382261d6ed20f5aa19aa5d43c42fe5ea1d46"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "someguy7654321", "rating": 2, "date": "2026-03-01", "title": null, "content": "Spoilers inside! Though I guess the title is a spoiler itself.\n\nOK, here we go:\n\nGet the eff out of here with that.\n\nThis movie was a freaking trainwreck. Though after part six, no expectations were had except \"ugh\" -- BUT, I did go see this on opening weekend with my wife, so who's the dumb ones? Exactly, us.\n\nWhere to begin... holy lord.\n\nIn part four and (I think) five, it's implied Sydney ends up with Mark Kincaid, the dude from part three. Her husband is referenced a few times as \"Mark\" and all that. In this movie, she is married to Mark, but a completely different Mark. What the hell is that?\n\nIn this movie, Sydney's daughter is 17, which means she would've been born already in part four, yet never mentioned. She would have been at most one and yet no one asked \"hey, how's your baby?\"\n\nScream movies spend an inordinate amount of time going over \"the rules.\" You know \"it's the boyfriend\" or \"it's someone from your past\" etc etc. Hyping up a reveal. In this movie, they do that, but then (almost as an F. U. to the audience) the killer is Ethan freaking Embry who had one scene and the dumb chick from the last season of \"You\" who also had like one or two scenes.\n\nShe's Sydney's next door neighbor AND mother of a teenage son. A son who is one of the killer's victims by the way. She's waaaaaaaay to relaxed about that too, like \"oh yeah, my kid, nope\" dude, what?\n\nThere is a fake out ghostface attack, and it's just a weird mental patient, that's unnecessary. Sure it drove the razor thin plot a little but my god.\n\nCourtney Cox and the twins from five and six are in this too, but they don't need to be. They contributed absolutely nothing and are only there as a \"hey! Remember us?\"\n\nThe main girl's boyfriend, sure is suspicious and even has AI videos of himself doing the threats from the killer. Again, never explained and he's killed off like two minutes later. What was the point of that?\n\nAnd the gore. Look, I get it... the younger crowd like \"Terrifier\" and crap like that, but this is Scream, that is not needed at all. In one scene, the killer puts a kid's head on a very sharp beer tap handle and his mouth is open and blood and beer flow out of his mouth. Sure, it elicited a laugh from some of the crowd, but that is the filmmakers trying too hard to compete with \"modern\" horror. Completely unnecessary.\n\nThe final kill on the dumb killer has her getting shot like 40 times and her face is just shredded into goo, again... why? Not needed.\n\nThis was just beyond awful."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "f4898a9e-66e9-462e-a599-fac27599fd55", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184413", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "9a20b99855263ea2dd8939ecbac032a27406607d3ae66a5b9c7c70cfea011855"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "masonwoods", "rating": 2, "date": "2026-03-03", "title": null, "content": "It had potential but wasted it more than you could possibly imagine. Absolute cornball trash with nothing but nostalgia bait. The opening made it seem promising. It was all downhill from there. Everyone is dumb, the \"twist\" made even less sense than the ones before. I would have rather seen FNAF 2 again than watch this boiling conglomerate of sadness and disappointment."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "498ff232-ea2d-4bfc-b20a-0a9ad9c4785b", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184413", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "9e45319cf3b3c58750cec0790fcdfb4d832153e16bbefea53afb069426f980d3"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "cadillac20", "rating": 5, "date": "2026-02-27", "title": null, "content": "30 years ago, Scream revitalized slasher horror with a witty, self-aware film that delivered genuine thrills and a good mystery to boot. Scream 7 seems like the other side of the hill. While it has the trademarks and some great kills/gore, it's also a tired chapter with what is easily the worst reveal of the entire franchise. I'm not even sure what they were thinking with all this. If Scream '22 and VI showed the franchise still had some fresh blood left to spill, 7 shows that the franchise has run out of steam.\n\nIt's great to see Sydney again, with Neve Campbell once again owing the film every time she's on screen, even she looks like she's done. Isabel May also does a good job as daughter Tatum, named after the character from the original movie. There's something endearing about the story revolving around one scream queen passing the baton on to the next generation. We got some of this from Scream '22, but here it's much more personal. Courtney Cox feels wasted here returning as Gale. Yeah, it's nice to see her, along with returning Chad and Mindy from the last two movies, but their presence feels forced for the sake of continuing tradition.\n\nThe kills are definitely a highlight, continuing the bloodier and more brutal nature set by '22. There's at least two here that are highlights of the entire franchise and may compete for best of the year. If much of the film feels tired, these are at least entertaining enough to make the film enjoyable. Sadly, almost all of it, the mystery, the personal connections, the nostalgia baiting, all feel almost completely undone by the ever climactic reveal. I thought '22 had weak reveals, but this is easily the worst of the franchise and I honestly can't believe everyone thought it would work. It gives the feeling that the franchise is played out and I now wonder what we may have had if the film had continued what was set by the previous film. Sadly, we'll never know, but my hope is that it's done."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "0fd8538d-783f-49c1-9d90-9fe8e0ebb526", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184413", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "15cdaa60ba8de059fa4214148981d346355a0ca191a6430e5c58aa9f7a04a7e8"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "pedroquintaoo", "rating": 7, "date": "2026-02-27", "title": null, "content": "For me, Scream is what the Avengers films are for Marvel fans. I grew up with this franchise - the rules, Roger L. Jackson's phone calls, the iconic characters, the shocking reveals. So I went into Scream 7 excited, but also slightly afraid of being disappointed.\n\nAnd that's exactly what happened. The film wins me over during the first two acts, but completely loses me in the third.\n\nThe opening scene is solid, even if it's not among the franchise's best. It has good pacing, clever dialogue, and effective jump scares. However, Ghostface burning down Stu Macher's house feels more theatrical than logical. From there, the film leans heavily on nostalgia, especially through Sidney receiving calls supposedly from Stu. The idea of AI manipulation versus a real return is interesting and timely, but it's a double-edged sword. It builds suspense while also stealing space from the classic Ghostface calls that define the saga. When this arc resolves, it does so quickly and without real impact.\n\nIsabel May is a strong addition as Sidney's daughter, and seeing Neve Campbell back with meaningful screen time feels right. The balance between the two generations works well, and their dynamic is one of the film's strengths. Unfortunately, the supporting cast lacks proper development. While more interesting than the group in Scream 5, the film doesn't build enough suspicion around them. That classic \"anyone could be the killer\" tension feels weaker here.\n\nOn the positive side, Ghostface is particularly brutal. The bar kill sequence is one of the most memorable horror moments I've seen in years. The tension works, the suspense is well constructed, and even the jump scares are carefully executed.\n\nThe real issue is the final act. The killer's identity and motivations feel forced and underdeveloped, and several narrative threads are wrapped up too quickly. For a franchise known for smart and surprising reveals, this ending feels like a step backward.\n\nStill, Scream 7 isn't a disaster. It entertains, delivers solid tension, and offers some strong moments. But it lacks the mystery and shocking reveal that define this saga. For fans like me, it's worth seeing in theaters - but it leaves the feeling that this seventh stab could have been much sharper."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "ff55535c-2613-4fd7-a648-d1766187afdf", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184413", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "ff9462e1a43e8da24b932999349580fd4fa7be95e24a576371c02b938e6c9531"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "umutoncul-66053", "rating": 7, "date": "2026-02-25", "title": null, "content": "Having just walked out of the theater, I can confidently say that Scream 7 is a remarkable achievement for a long-running horror franchise. While the film pays a beautiful, nostalgic homage to the original 1996 masterpiece, it manages to remain an entirely authentic and fresh experience. It references the classic tropes and plot structures of the first film, but it doesn't lean on them as a crutch; instead, it uses them as a foundation to build something much more intricate.\n\nThis entry feels significantly more interesting and daring than its immediate predecessors. The narrative is layered with more characters and complex subplots, making the story feel denser and more rewarding. Unlike the last few installments, the \"predictable\" slasher moments are surprisingly scarce here-if you watch closely, the film rewards your attention with subtle details that hint at the larger mystery.\n\nThe decision to have Kevin Williamson (the brilliant mind behind the screenplays of Scream 1 & 2) both write and direct was the best choice the studio could have made. There is no one more qualified to helm the 7th chapter of this legacy. Beyond the multi-layered storytelling, his directorial touch brings unique camera angles and seamless transitions to the horror sequences. The \"clich\u00e9s\" are almost non-existent, replaced by high-quality suspense and genuine tension.\n\nCompared to the last two films, I left the cinema feeling much more satisfied. It's a high-quality sequel that respects its roots while evolving the \"Whodunit\" formula for a modern audience. A must-watch for any Ghostface fan."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "69fbc319-e368-4326-b83c-e968d1b0e1bf", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184413", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "2161990741bc019b5be1c043f48a15b3c47c6c4ad0b6c3229e5f9b0d932209a4"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "EndlessHorrors", "rating": 2, "date": "2026-03-01", "title": null, "content": "I had a feeling after all the terrible decisions Spyglass made that resulted in Jenna Ortega and the director leaving that this movie would be trash and let me just tell you I was not wrong.\n\nI know they spent a lot of money rewriting and reworking the script after Ortega's exit and that money was not spent well.\n\nNev fell flat in her role and the actress that played Tatum was just meh. I couldn't have cared less about what happened to the characters.\n\nI'd normally give such a poorly written and poorly executed film a 1 star but I love Matthew Lillard and was glad to temporarily see him so it got the extra star for him. If only this movie actually deserved someone of Matthew Lillard's talents.\n\nTLDR: even if you're a long time fan of the franchise, I'd recommend against this movie. It'll only disappoint and leave a sour taste behind. Now I'm not even sure I could enjoy a rewatch of the originals."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "ed1b8522-4bb7-4961-a927-3b81b3364855", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184413", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "28905b8f7a80405ab020bd8537055a2ee276ecd69ab85bb7a2d09e56b8e1ca72"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "Masami-J", "rating": null, "date": "2026-03-02", "title": null, "content": "Scream 7 is : The narrative is seen as a tired repetition of clich\u00e9s, overly dependent on nostalgia and lacking real tension.\n\nNumerous chronological errors and plot holes that irritate longtime fans.\n\nLack of original ideas, making the film a purely commercial venture that adds nothing to the franchise.\n\nA bad film; perhaps seven Scream Movies is already too much; there was no need for so many films; it's now a tired franchise devoid of ideas. It's now a tired franchise devoid of ideas.it's now a tired franchise devoid of ideas."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "5a369ec0-d6d8-4126-80e2-3136f9514db3", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184413", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "552a1218c54f217c29c51bf2ae5c7448e5b5eb82c7147508385ae7b88f49352a"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "j0hn22", "rating": 10, "date": "2026-02-26", "title": null, "content": "First of all, I have to say that I'm a massive and longtime fan of the Scream franchise and as you can all imagine, it was obvious that I was gonna watch this movie at the cinema. When I first watched the official trailer of the movie I liked it and I had high expectations about it. Eventually, I watched the movie and I can confirm that it was as GOOD as I had imagined. When I first read the movie synopsis, I thought it was very interesting and mysterious, but I wouldn't consider it an innovative movie because it's concept was similar to the previous movies. The storyline was very well-written and well-explained, even though it was simple and easy to understand. The characters were very interesting, well-developed and likeable. Regarding the \"fresh blood\" I have to say that all of them were great and I really liked the new friend group, even though I wish they had more screen time. The casting choices were great and their performances were incredible, I mean each actor/actresses did a great job of portraying their characters. The filming location of the movie was beautiful and gladly, the new town that this movie was filmed was perfect. I have to admit, it was a very scary movie and there were many jumpscares (even though, most of them were kinda predictable lol). Gladly, it was a very intense movie from start to finish, extremely suspenseful and there were many great mini attack/chase scenes during the movie. I mean, the opening scene, the auditorium scene, the bar sequence and Tatum's chase scene were the highlights of the movie. Regarding the killcount, I have to say that the death scenes were very bloody, brutal and gory AF. Also, this movie had many creative kills and there was one particular death scene that was insane AF, I'm not joking. In my opinion, the opening scene was very promising, scary, intense, brutal and I really enjoyed it, so much. The 2nd act was something like a love letter to the OG fans, since it was full of callbacks to the first movie, some great death scenes, nice mini attack scenes and funny moments. Regarding the 3rd act, I have to say that I have mixed feelings about it. I mean, the killer reveal was definitely unpredictable, but I don't think it was a memorable killer reveal and the motive was kinda mehh... Anyway, at least it was a great movie and I had so much fun of watching it! Last but not least, the cinematography and the score of the movie were both beautiful and very well done. Overall, \"Scream 7\" was a great addition to this iconic slasher franchise that was giving me major H20: 20 Years Later movie vibes, it had a great and memorable killcount, perfect chase scenes, funny moments, it was visually beautiful and I would definitely recommend it to everyone!"}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "aaf45bce-c2e2-4997-ad82-9089e9104c73", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184413", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "75115b5220ff6ccb6fc7d5c2cce80dd92cae81f32286190b287f0585c2b0e6d4"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "dclay85", "rating": 7, "date": "2026-03-01", "title": null, "content": "I think it was good. I was entertained and interested in Sidney's story since we haven't really met her family before. I like how the killers actually scare me with all the appearing then hiding when you think they might still be there, and like popping out when you don't expect it. I'm not a huge slasher fan but Scream has always been one slasher film that I actually like. Maybe because it's kind of funny and the characters fight back and aren't the stupidest people ever.\n\nAnyway, I saw a lot of bad reviews so I wanted to say it isn't so! And I don't think this was bad. The story didn't need to be told? I mean none of this needs to happen if only people didn't continue to become fixated on stalking and trying to kill Sidney and friends for literal decades. It's just another crazy person's attempt. If you like Scream, you'll like this I think, if you're a superfan and know all the details and lore, maybe those are the people who'd nitpick."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "f51b48b0-da75-45df-b2c6-dcbf53aff766", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184413", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "5a84d578aaf103a96ba0d2063657f6dc026d28ac5aa26640de2bb8439a40ec20"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "slightlymad22", "rating": 7, "date": "2026-03-03", "title": null, "content": "I just got out of Scream 7.\n\nI have to admit, I thought Courtney Cox died in Scream 6 and I didn't recognise two of the returning characters, for the last two movies. So that say a lot about my interest in this long running franchise lol\n\nIt is very heavy on its nostalgia bait (right down to the exact same dialogue) and is very meta. The third act was embarassingly weak, but the first two acts were enjoyable enough (despite some awful dialogue). I really liked the opening, although the trailer spoilt in and what happened to the first kill being a somewhat big cameo??\n\nIt was good to be back in a small town setting and there are some good, creative kills, but lack of character development, stop us actually caring about the characters, but there is some genuine tension at times.\n\nOf the cast Neve Campbell does a nice job and she shares some good scenes with Courtney Cox, Isabel May was good as Sydney's daughter as was Anna Camp. I didn't actually think anyone was bad.\n\nIs it top tier Scream, no?? Is it as bad as some reviews say?? Also no."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "0eb7fdf7-cd07-41a3-92db-d031db323266", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184413", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "77b92a7e17710954b875c6661b0f34bceab044ad3ab3e0960e6457d204043c94"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "sgildea-78306", "rating": 8, "date": "2026-02-26", "title": null, "content": "Scream 7 is a blast. A great movie to watch at the cinema and fortunately I was at a showing with an audience who were into it!\n\nThe opening is a memorable one with great tension and jump scares.\n\nMuch better than the previous two movies.\n\nSydney Prescott is back and it's another good performance from Neve Campbell who has absolutely nailed her character.\n\nWe meet her daughter and her friends who all have their shady ways!\n\nIt's a good way to keep us guessing who ghostface(s)is/are this time.\n\nThe kills are violent and much bloodier than previous entries.\n\nBut are also kind of fun (if you like that sort of thing)!\n\nThis movie perhaps doesn't reach classic standards like Scream 1 and 2 but it's action packed, tense on occasion and is pretty funny. Especially when Gail Weathers turns up!\n\nAlthough she is underused and a bit of stronger writing for the character is needed next time.\n\nOverall this is a treat for Scream fans."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "12722bd8-e092-48a6-9260-f55a50ac21e3", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184413", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "ed47ef0ec30174591cfbc8b841dc9463449c6ee618108310cbcf0f840d465b62"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "scotthodom", "rating": 1, "date": "2026-02-27", "title": null, "content": "Scream 7 is easily the worst of the franchise and is continuing a disappointing and disturbing trend in 2026, which is a string of bad and lackluster movies. The great films in 2026 are few and far between. The reason this film doesn't work to me is because of the actual Ghostface choice(s). The big reveal and motives behind why are lacking and weak. The magic and fun scares are gone from the franchise. Might be time to stop new entries in this franchise or if it must continue, it needs new eyes and voices to breathe new life and scares."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "17725fa6-d417-4da6-b9a7-3f64060dc493", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184413", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "064bebc68131a801c5d4590b189cf4192e72418f508fda8389c727132b9b4132"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "Allstar734", "rating": 1, "date": "2026-02-28", "title": null, "content": "What was bad?\n\n-opening literally exact same as the trailer and it wasnt good enough to see twice\n\n-Sydney married to a police officer and it being joel mchale isnt clicking right with me....\n\n-Sydney's daughter's bf climbs through window like sydney doesnt have a security system by this point? Plz hoe\n\n-Too many nostalgia moments like bro think of something new....not remind us how better the old films are...\n\n-The daughters bf literally bringing up \"have you seen the new ghostface docs\" like it wasnt the most tragic thing in her life...\n\n-A girl gets murdered while Sydneys daughter was at drama rehearsal....there was like 10 people in the room and then 30 secs later its just ghostface...? Bro please stop\n\n--Sydneys daughter showing no emotion and literally cuddling with her boyfriend in the theater chairs when her classmate died 20 seconds ago and is hanging in front of them....im so done with this movie\n\n-Joel Mchale wrestling ghostface down a hill feels like an SNL skit\n\nThis movie is just a cash grab. It wasn't screened in advance for a reason..."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "893e768b-b820-485d-aeb5-881d2ca610a4", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184413", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "e653b338e2454bb3a4d38c81ac6e5c36f86456557d6881ea58c2b2bbdddce5cf"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "rgkarim", "rating": 7, "date": "2026-02-27", "title": null, "content": "LIKES: The Jokes For The Most Part The Character Development Of The Leads Shot Beautifully Decent Suspense At Times The Acting Is Fine Nostalgia Rings Out Savage Kills Continue For Series Pace Is Good Summary: Scream has always been ahead of the game since its creation, making fun of the horror genre, but still making a horror film out of it. Those jokes sink in quite well, coming back with a bite far more vicious than previous entities. The seventh installment is merciless in its insults. The self-indulgence of the jokes had me laughing up a storm, the extreme humor hitting at just the right moments with a well-timed quip, muttering, or some clever joke to drop the hammer of Scream's humor. You have to appreciate a darker comedic tone, filled with aggressive language and horrifying actions, to fully appreciate it, but if you can, you'll find yourself rewarded with quite a film.\n\nPast the comedy, the movie continues to appreciate its roots, diving back into the violent thriller we know this slasher to be. Scream 7 did not get blunted by all the political mess, instead embracing more of the new age technology to unleash Ghostface's wrath with as much savagery as they could muster. Moments of intense suspense are decorated with close calls as the new killer is trying to hack their way past any person to reach their goals. Some decent fights, standoffs, and games of hide-and-seek accomplish much, all with some of the most chilling (and cheesy) finishers that had the audience reeling. The new age technology brings great cinematography to keep things as hectic as possible, and the carnage is filled with that scream vibe you are looking for in this tried and true franchise. Nostalgia is very heavy in this film, and it seems to repair the damage mentioned earlier, and in a way, the movie worked by being able to tie the classic and modern together.\n\nAmidst all of this is decent character development, primarily through the two leads of Sidney and Tatum. This duo is going to get much of the screen time and serve as the focal points of advancing the story past the simple fight for survival. I found relevance in Sidney's story, and appreciated them trying to give her new levels past what has been a broken record on repeat from film to film. While it doesn't quite reinvent the wheel, the new tale is the next logical step in a story like this, and I liked the surprising depth Neve was able to bring. May's character is Tatum, and the daughter started annoying and clich\u00e9, but eventually managed to give me more than I expected. May brought the right amount of emotional backing, and I liked the way she evolved with the character, and I liked how they fashioned someone a bit more realistic, but not just stuck in one character arc. Together, they were able to launch a lot of the things I liked from this element, and feel this dynamic duo accomplished much with their acting. The rest of the group does a fine job as well, with Courteney Cox having some solid line delivery to bring that heat as only Gale Weathers can. And all of this works at a pace that was entertaining, but not too fast to cut the storytelling down too much to be frustrating.\n\nDISLIKES: The Jokes Get Old After A While The Character Balance Is Off The Mystery Element Is Lacking Predictable For The Most Part The Cursing Gets A Bit Much The Revelation Is A Stretch Summary: However, the movie is still all about the extremes, which sometimes got a bit out of hand for me. For one thing, the jokes get old after a while. The meta-humor becomes a running joke that I kind of got bored with, and after recently rewatching most of the Scream series, I was at my limit with the continuous badgering and jokes. Throw in the language getting a bit out of hand to the point that vocabulary becomes very limited, and you once again lose me quickly in that type of humor. These two elements can be a bit intense, and without being ready for that all over again, you might find this limitation enough to avoid this film.\n\nPast this, the story element still hasn't quite found the full splendor that we used to get with the first trilogy and the recent two films. Scream 7 is torn between the two worlds enough to make the story feel a bit blander than I had wanted, sacrificing the character development we were getting with Screams 5 and 6, and trying to fall too hard back into the old trilogy. To some degree, it does accomplish some good, but I think this tale was a bit calmer and clich\u00e9 than most might have wanted. I found the mystery element lacking, and was able to predict most of the twists and identities of those involved with the movie. I found the big reveal a bit too much of a stretch, and finding it either a very grandiose poke at modern times, or trying too hard to be that Soap Opera-like hyper drama that seems to be very popular these days. Unfortunately, the character balance is still missing for me, as new and old characters feel somewhat wasted and too bland compared to the past people who tried to fend off Ghostface. Sure, the opening sequence victims, this is expected, but the rest of the crew felt lost and pushed to the back, with only these trivial moments giving them any merit. It felt like this was a very assertive means to throw you off, but I can say the other films were much more accomplished at juggling all the characters. Finally, this film may have some very extravagant kills that can be cheesy, but they are able to do some very disturbing elements to the film, so please use caution before venturing to see it.\n\nThe VERDICT: Scream 7 turned out better on many levels than I had anticipated from all the drama it faced during production. Despite not extending on the story I was starting to enjoy, it found a space between both worlds that should satisfy both spectrums of fans. Loaded with the visuals, storytelling, and character approach of the new and the nostalgia, campiness, and characters of the old, Scream 7 has almost the best of both worlds in this Thriller/Horror/Comedy amalgamation. I had a lot of fun with much of the movie, especially the character development being prominent, but not getting in the way of the primary gimmick of the franchise, and all in a pace that works to support that. But past the creative kills and self-deprecating humor is a film that may still be too lost in nostalgia to be an improvement. There are still some heavily contrived plot points, more so than the previous installments, and they get a bit silly in their attempt to follow the rules established by this franchise. The violence and cursing get a bit too much, and the jokes are sometimes a tad too forced into your face to remain funny the whole time. In addition, the revelation was a bit underwhelming for me, but that was because of the predictability of the movie and the obvious foreshadowing. Finally, the character use is one of the weaker elements of this film, as new and old characters don't quite have the full integration I wanted, several of them seeming to be set up for new stories to tell as the franchise tries once again to pass the torch. Factoring all this in, I think the movie is still worth a trip to the theater, and many very enthusiastic fans will enjoy getting to see this one in the splendor of the theater.\n\nMy scores are: Mystery/Horror/Slasher: 7.5 Movie Overall: 7.0."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "3c0edd76-f3b7-4f08-88d1-ae8d0c9694eb", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184413", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "771baaa7e7fed7dc78d76e563132053d25a6d251ff4d99b3377a219ad2ceb09c"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "sarakuralexx", "rating": 10, "date": "2026-02-26", "title": null, "content": "Relentless pace, great character development, the theater erupting in applause with Gale's entrance. 7 is the Scream 5 we all deserved.\n\nWhat a pleasant surprise: this is a franchise built on suspense, not what 5 and 6 tried to be.\n\nI absolutely loved Gale and Sidney in this, and cannot wait to see them in 8."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "2d74b9c4-ad80-48e7-9231-7ce3d5f250fb", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184413", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "7842451288e6bc512bdb5b5d2048d71fae64947799714e01b204b55ee546d377"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "greatdiscipleofslaanesh", "rating": 1, "date": "2026-02-27", "title": null, "content": "People were all excited for this movie. I was excited too. Stu is going to be in this movie. Turns out Stu isn't in this movie. It is false advertising. The Ghostfaces have the worst motivations for being Ghostface. They are poorly written characters. Everything feels so contrived and pointless. This entire movie is bad fanfiction."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "218c08fd-6bd2-4fe1-b57b-1e80a1826049", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184413", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "b382217e25d741f8cd551b66bbbace9e3de339876b3b5ed2b5f224df50f54cab"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "soryu-483-575512", "rating": 1, "date": "2026-03-02", "title": null, "content": "This movie sucks. The storylime Does not fit. Gail disappeared from the second half and instead a lot of people is killed with no purpose, so quickly that you can't have any kind of bond with them. Some killings are visually a '70s bmovie. Also the ghostfaces are some strangers taken from the street as they were passing near the cameras. I am shocked on how much I hated this movie."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "9a7dd932-1195-471b-a057-21177e5a2ba5", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184918", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "da8d2e35fae8e8c18fbc6a6fb5338a714249c744500f5a131525135095bcb2e8"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "Iknowbetterthanyou", "rating": 2, "date": "2026-03-03", "title": null, "content": "Why do they try so hard but can't seem to alleviate the cheese? Courtney Cox is absolutely horrid. Shows up and brings up as many corny lines as she can. It's like the script hands her a checklist of callbacks and forced one-liners and says, \"Go get 'em.\" Instead of feeling sharp and self-aware like the original did, the humor just lands flat and desperate.\n\nThe franchise used to balance meta commentary with genuine tension, but here it feels like they're winking at the audience every five minutes just to remind us we're in on the joke. The scares are predictable, the reveals feel rushed, and the emotional beats don't have time to breathe. You can practically see the formula working overtime behind the scenes."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "258d9f3e-80f0-469e-96f3-f0fd58034fe7", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184918", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "4e8012aa639171cc3b96e03d4625117682f94d23484dc6e80427f1286bcb7786"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "maryelizabetthh760", "rating": 10, "date": "2026-03-01", "title": null, "content": "Amazing fantastic as always. Big fan of scream franchise since the beginning. Love every single one.\n\nLoved seeing so many originals. Great story, plot twists and reveals as always.\n\nThere better be a number 8 in the planning stage already.\n\nAnd after #8, 50 more movies.\n\nFav franchise ever.\n\nNever gets old."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "f9857d37-cf47-4836-a2cd-351e109cffbe", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184918", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "a1e50e73bba232780b6f2c07fcc2c724b29116bbad6283ef1439634ef734972c"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "KEV-Yb", "rating": 4, "date": "2026-02-26", "title": null, "content": "They tried WAY too hard to make this movie into something newer and more shocking... but they failed just as hard.\n\nFirst of all, they failed to move on from Melissa and Jenna. How unfair it was to fire Melissa f\u00f6r supporting Palestine is a whole other discussion but at least MENTION their characters.\n\nThe AI-storyline was also wack. I get the message behind it (dangers of AI) but it wasn't thought out pretty well. They built up a Stu-being-alive-reveal the whole movie and in the end, he was only AI? Bffr...\n\nThe killers and the reveals were weak and confusing. Especially the doctor guy. See how I refer to him as \"doctor guy?\" Yeah, because he was in 1 or 2 scenes before and no indication of him being a suspect. Jessica was the best killer in this one in my opinion, and even she lacks depth and makes zero sense.\n\nThe deaths were cool tho... but that's about it."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "cfbec540-8098-4700-81c8-1565a5e5e5c7", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184918", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "8afbd26f95ccf7eaeb596cb514c4131709745ba5b0cc6b3fb2fb75f8ade821d4"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "tim_lofling", "rating": 4, "date": "2026-02-25", "title": null, "content": "Very dissapointed, but not surprised.\n\nScream has always had a sort of glint in the eye. A charm. A vibe. Until now.\n\nThis movie felt soulless. It felt as though they were trying to put in references just to get them in rather than them actually having meaning.\n\nThe reveal of Gale, Chad and Mindy was top notch and I loved it. But after that they barely had screentime. And when they wereon the screen, it was empty. Mindy who always lights up a room, had great energy and charisma is now some wannabe news anchor? She would never go for that. And Chad just barely existed. They probably had a contract for 3 movies and had to be in it. Atleast that's how it felt.\n\nI understand they avoided mentioning Sam and Tara but come on.. Half of the core four are there but nothing basically? One snarky comment?\n\nThe movie played all out in the beginning but didn't gain traction or just didn't do anything with the early ramp they did. Very weak ending which barely felt relevant or in line with any of the movies.\n\nWeak movie in the series, but kind of expected after the whole behind the scenes drama. There's no magic in this like in previous entries."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "cf65c146-4de1-435f-bec7-a86f8ed0157f", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184918", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "8aebdb80d60cac005ac380a5b6775c610aa415957b6a61cdafc8078054132849"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "joshhilmeyer", "rating": 1, "date": "2026-03-02", "title": null, "content": "It's not that hard to write a half decent story for this franchise however they keep mucking it up. Even with a good story though these actors fail repeatedly. This must be some nepo situation because the main final girl, her boyfriend and her other friend are so bad it made me want them to die. The only satisfying part was watching some of the annoying characters die but it was kind of ruined by the sheer ridiculousness of their deaths. The main final girl is egregiously bad, someone is paying good money to give her a career cause she cannot act her way out of a paper bag and somehow landed this huge role. They make the first movies look oscar worthy. The villains were also insultingly bad and I wish they would stop casting that woman from the accapella films who tried her best to branch out in You the series but fails to come off as anything but annoying. Lets all forget this absolute rank mess and move on with our lives with no memory of it."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "f72893d5-0b47-402e-931e-8a3680756ed8", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184918", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "376172d95a8072a85945736d28c791b8c2cf94aa7f0b6a5abb5d606ac29fb536"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "psgorio", "rating": 4, "date": "2026-03-04", "title": null, "content": "Scream VII broke my heart on a few levels, but that's OK. I expected it to do so at some point during the runtime of the movie so it wasn't a total surprise when it completely and utterly shat the bed in the final act.\n\nIt had so much potential too. Shame on the writers for relying on shameless topical elements in this day and age to further the plot and try and have some type of wow factor by thinking they are subverting expectations that they were going for and in the end just ended up having a head scratcher of a final reveal when you find out who the killer actually is.\n\nWhat I did appreciate some things from within this clusterboink of a sequel. I really loved the relationship Neve Campbell's character Sydney had with her daughter. The acting between the two was pretty on point and had some element of depth to it and sincerity. Sydney has always been a strong scream queen for 30 years strong now and her daughter was vulnerable yet strong willed, wanting to learn how to hold her own in case the horrors that beset her mother ever crept up on her family again. With that being said, they could've done so much more with the plot in regards to their relationship and how they could have had to take some sharp twist and turns. But naturally they didn't. I also appreciated some of the cameos from past films, albeit done so in a kind of cheap way.\n\nI also really enjoyed some of the gruesome kills that were showcased. Some of them were really on that Terrifier level of gore. But overall as a whole, I just really cannot recommend this movie because it's just too much of a poop show when it boils down to the plot or lack thereof in my opinion. I really think that this franchise needs to go on a nice long hiatus sooner than later as it kind of peaked for me with Scream VI and that really isn't saying much because that movie to me was already teetering on the edge of overkill."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "c83b29d2-818a-4ebe-871f-965ecbe4d323", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184918", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "dc30aba626d089e922721eed0796c3f137cf9255dc4ae731afe2aed88d3bde4b"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "cruise01", "rating": 4, "date": "2026-03-03", "title": null, "content": "2 out of 5 stars.\n\nScream 7 is a bad slasher film that is the weakest with the films in the franchise making a huge turn in becoming something else.\n\nThe plot is forgettable. Follows the ghost face killer coming back to go after Sidney (Neve Campbell) and her young adult daughter.\n\nThe franchise was turning around a bit with overcoming the dumb cliches with characters making the stupid decisions that got themselves killed. Well this film the script falls back to those cliches with characters making stupid decisions. Several films from now and characters have yet to learn the rules and logic when facing a killer. It's like there first time seeing one. Taking forever to run out or taking forever to pull the gun trigger. Clearly no one is smart in this film and Sidney is no better. Being one of the survivors since the original and several films. Still has not taught her a lesson. The script fails at that. The direction is a bit dull. The film does have some gory kills. The twists with the killers identity was eh and not surprising. The killers being revealed is forgettable. The concept of several cameos was tedious. Didn't make one surpising shock moment. The cast was eh. Especially the supporting casts that usually gets killed off. They were all forgettable.\n\nOverall, it was a bad film in the franchise that took steps backward to being good."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "7eb05c60-3c07-4f44-b7c6-296164902b5b", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184918", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "56d8102d85ab9ac15667d5ee9292693d4ed7ce9fa4c08b212e16486486902742"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "Jelisei", "rating": 3, "date": "2026-03-02", "title": null, "content": "I was hoping they'd meta-ironically reinterpret the original. I guess they tried. Dramatically failed.\n\nBoring. That's the worst part.\n\nNo good jokes. No good acting. No clever twists. I kept waiting for something - anything - to grab onto. It never happened.\n\nMaybe part of the problem is that I'm not a hardcore fan of the franchise. I was probably supposed to feel something when certain characters showed up. I didn't. When the killer(s) was revealed, my reaction was literally: \"Who?\" I don't know these people. I don't care why they're doing it. There's no emotional or narrative weight behind it.\n\nAnd the fake intrigue attempts? Painful.\n\n\"Look! This guy looks suspicious! He might be the killer...\" \n* nope, just kidding.\n\n\n\"Look! This one looks sus--\" \n* and he's dead in a second.\n\n\nThat's not clever misdirection. That's lazy bait-and-switch.\n\nAs meta-horror? Empty.\n\nAs slasher? Mid.\n\nAs a movie? Forgettable."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "6b03cfde-95cb-4d44-8c75-3553ad1d4e82", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184918", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "76b24c94d3d3700ce02b936de4508a6e209f76e6d253924fd8c8340b1767064c"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "Beyondtherain", "rating": 10, "date": "2026-02-27", "title": null, "content": "This is the most entertaining movie I've seen in years...I grew up with Scream and this was so much better than the trailers...the trailers looked very tame and same ol same ol, but wow this movie was brutal and amazing, its the most different feeling Scream movie and i love part 6 but this might beat...I had no idea who ghostface was ln this fiIm, l kinda figured lt out but wow...it's never who you think lt is...the My bloody valentine homage kiII was PERFECT and brutaI...The Home invasion scene was insane...I love how Ghostface moves like an Actual ghost and phantom in this fiIm, Ghostface IS the shadow on the wall...a few scenes Ghostface is literally doing what michael myers does, that ghostly supernatural type of movement...so thanks to the boycotters...this movie was better than anything the Carpenter Sisters storyline could be...Jenna Ortega, Melissa Barrera, you are sadIy N0T MlSSED...THIS WAS A REAL SCREAM. It is Refreshing and Revitalized...Thank you Kevin Williamson."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "19916edf-ef5a-4471-b3d7-0d70e7d3ccfa", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184918", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "e2bd19d40d53bac7099d5e31601425fd9621cb383d676c29ba37312222f314fa"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "horrorules", "rating": 7, "date": "2026-02-28", "title": null, "content": "I promised myself I wouldn't write any more reviews since, for no reason, the \"dear\" site managers deleted some of my reviews and didn't even publish others (in fact, I'm not sure this review will ever see the light of day), but I'll try anyway.\n\nAs the title suggests, I liked this seventh chapter. It's objectively better than chapters 5 and 6, even if it's obviously not at the level of the first 4 films directed by the legendary Wes. However, this is a more serious and mature film, with its flaws, especially the ending, and on this I agree with most viewers. The two killers are the worst in the saga and aren't explored or developed at all. Marco is anonymous, he appears for 2 minutes during the film, which could also be a good and innovative thing for the saga. In fact, in the previous films, the various killers were seen quite a bit throughout the film, and Marco is played by Ethan Embry, who is a talented actor and well-suited to this role. However, he should have had more space in the ending and explained his motive a little, but instead, a few moments after he was revealed as the killer, he is killed by Sidney in a very hasty manner. Jessica is a weak villain, and her motive is too convoluted and unclear. It's a shame, because the rest of the film is very funny and brutal. Some of the murders, especially the girl on the stage and the boy impaled in the beer dispenser, are among the best in the franchise.\n\nBut let's get to the most important aspect, the one that really made me appreciate the film: the mockery it makes of those toxic, ridiculous, ignorant, and pathetic fans who for years have been stressing everyone out with their absurd theories about Stu's resurrection. According to these \"geniuses,\" it was perfectly plausible that a human being who takes about 10 stab wounds and ends up with his skull crushed by a CRT TV and electrocuted to death could survive. And when you tried, even politely, to tell them it was an absurd theory, you were insulted. Well, now what do you have to say, you clowns? Now you're not talking anymore? I'll always be grateful to Williamson for shutting them up forever. These people are the reason so many movies suck these days. People who don't care about quality want to be indulged in their stupidity. It was nice to see Stu again. Lillard is a great actor (sorry, Quentin, but you should apologize to him). It was also nice to see Roman again, one of the best killers, the brilliant criminal mastermind behind everything and the only lone killer (I'm tired of multiple killers; this time I would have preferred a single killer like in the third film). It was also nice to see Dewey again. I don't care about Nancy Loomies, I never liked her as a killer.\n\nI'll conclude by saying that the film is very good, but maybe it's time to call it a day and not push my luck. 7 movies are enough. Ghostface has left his mark on history, and it's time for him to enjoy his well-deserved retirement."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "0619cf9a-6467-41ce-81b1-af56714da014", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184918", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "f065758912d2191f6df19e85f37a05de9eb20cd3ea4a814bea29e3c30ba0cded"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "TheHighEvolutionary", "rating": 1, "date": "2026-02-28", "title": null, "content": "When Meta-Horror Becomes Unintentional Self-Parody\n\nScream 7 confirms what many feared: the franchise is no longer evolving: it is self-parodying without realizing it. The film attempts to revive the meta formula that once defined the series, but does so without narrative rigor and without genuine tension.\n\nThe major issue lies in the screenplay.\n\nThe dramatic structure feels incoherent, with motivations that appear and disappear according to the needs of the moment rather than the psychology of the characters. Suspense is nearly absent because the internal rules of the universe are no longer respected. When a horror film loses its internal logic, it loses its fear factor.\n\nThe direction feels rushed and lacking a distinct visual identity. The stalking sequences, essential to the franchise's DNA, are staged mechanically, without a gradual build-up of tension. The pacing is paradoxical: artificially fast during action scenes, yet flat and inert during dialogue. Ironically, the film is so devoid of momentum that I found myself falling asleep in the theater, a devastating verdict for a horror film.\n\nThe tone is confused. It works neither as authentic horror nor as intelligent satire. The humor lacks timing, and the meta element feels recycled from previous installments without offering a new perspective on the genre. The result resembles a commercial extension of a brand rather than a film born of artistic necessity.\n\nScream 7 is not merely below expectations, it is symptomatic of a franchise that has lost its direction, though not its budget. A disappointing experience and, ultimately, a waste of time."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "fb77f4f3-728c-4db8-b5d8-c6c1b663141d", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184918", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "730439dfe1f8e1e22fea24c9d78f418451c02120b20a595d65ea647fd6ba2ae9"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "Jimmoviesreviews", "rating": 10, "date": "2026-02-26", "title": null, "content": "What's your favourite scary movie? Scream 7 is back and still going strong. Somehow it managed to make the mother saves her daughter storyline not boring at all Sydney had enough after all those year ,just dont mess with original It couldn't get any worst than 6,the Carpenter sisters storyline didn't last long . Melissa held good the last two movies But Neve,is the Scream franchise,after Ghostface.. Don't start the whole ,The killers are getting predictable Of course they are after 7 movies , it's pretty easy to tell that someone from the cast will be the killer. My new ranking is Scream 1,2,3,7,5,6,4. I hope they keep them coming till we see Scream goes time travel and in Space."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "4af2dfa9-f112-4acb-a2a4-a3c7611f45e2", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184918", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "9f7faa061149bf1b3df085992c98d77f97a386a91f90860b38088d0048a48ba2"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "pckuhn-45718", "rating": 2, "date": "2026-03-01", "title": null, "content": "This is an insult to the fans, worst reveal in motivation for the killers ever I'm not sure, even if they try, they could top it, Kevin Williamson is a writer not a director that was made obvious through this poor production, the fact they would troll the fans with stu is a mockery, this whole thing was a giant letdown. How does it even have 6 out of 10?"}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "bbfe09d2-1062-4741-af78-ef6d748b6c45", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184918", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "1f5c985b8e09ba9bff90ca7dd7a3bc316108631d700d031124feb5a0f39c4278"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "tythebaker", "rating": 2, "date": "2026-03-04", "title": null, "content": "Scream 1 was iconic as a horror-comedy. By the time we arrive at Scream 7, the charm is long since diluted. To quote Peter Griffin \"it insists upon itself\". Instead of poking fun at tropes and cliches of the horror genre, this movie makes fun of \"Scream Movies\" while sticking to the same formula.\n\nI'm in the theater writing this, but nobody cares because nobody is here in the theater with me.\n\nDon't bother."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "3ffabc8d-6621-40df-97a9-296d2505b9f1", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184918", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "bdf67f0dc56d9680c35c6836a89b1636327aff2336146c2a4f6bf01d99fe46ad"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "geno-young", "rating": 9, "date": "2026-02-28", "title": null, "content": "NO SPOILERS: \"Scream 7\" has entered the top three echelon of \"Scream Films.\" It was fresh, refreshing, and honestly the most fun I've ever had in a movie theater. And my new favorite in-theater applause moment is Gale's iconic entrance (If you know, you know) ! The whole place went NUTS!!!\n\nWit: Check!\n\n-Innards (Guts): Check, check!\n\n-Suspense: Check, check, check!\n\n-Sidney Prescott: Quadruple CHECK!!!!\n\nThis film has it ALL. You can chalk up any bad reviews to rage/politics/personal grievance, or a combination of the three. Any hollow, bad-faith reviews should be resoundingly ignored, because nothing in this film warrants them. One of the things I liked about the film was the way that it continuously tricked the audience like ANY good \"Scream\" film does. There were times where you had no clue what was real, and what wasn't (I must admit, I sussed out the technology angle early on).\n\nThe film really took a page out of the recent \"Halloween\" trilogy's book by showing the generational ripple effect of trauma. BUT, Williamson is an infinitely better writer than any of the people who worked on those films, so he handled the trauma angle superbly. Surprisingly, I thoroughly enjoyed Chad and Mindy for the first time around; after being annoyed to no end by them in the past and begging for a swift, bloody end to their cringeworthy performances. Further proof that no character is irredeemable, as long as the WRITER is strong.\n\nThe thing that I disliked the most was the reveal. I feel like the film built up perfectly to that point, just to leave the audience a bit confused, and deflated. Once the bottom dropped out towards the end, the stakes were definitely lowered, but it still finished in a strong fashion. But up to the end, the film DRIPPED with soon to be iconic moments! I think that Kevin Williamson has outdone himself, and I cannot wait to see what mayhem awaits in \"Scream 8!\" Get out and SEE IT! It beats \"5\" & \"6\" (which I liked) in every way!"}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "0eacec91-8dbc-42e9-8b1c-f0b4d55651b5", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184918", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "1bed52b771085942c7e09f3f35f7bb8d7562e1cd144cb847d298f3b6b4f5c65e"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "ardakkaya-77177", "rating": 1, "date": "2026-03-03", "title": null, "content": "Scream 7 is the worst movie in the scream franchise. The plot of this movie is Sidney and her daughter Tatum are moved a new town and Sidney's past haunts her after 30 years later and that past is Stu Macher. When I was watching the movie I was so hyped that Stu is alive because he is different than the other Ghosface's in the franchise because Stu killed all those people just for sport. In the act three they show us that Stu is not alive and it was just AI or deepfake. Then they show us that the old dead characters like Nancy Loomis, Roman Bridger and Dewey. I think they knew the movie is going to flop and they thought that they can milk the fans with fan service but no we are not in early 2010's the movie will criticize by the plot not the fan service. My second reason that I hate this movie is the kills and gore in this movie. In scream franchise Ghostface killers are like sharks in the movie because first they analyze your moves and they try to scare their victims then they kill their victim. But this movie thinks it self that this movie is Terrifier. In this movie the kills are way more gory than the other movies in the franchise. This time killer just attacks like a brainless maniac. And my last reason that I hate this movie is the killers in this movie. When they showed us who the killer is my reaction was like \" why\" because in the series the killer is always comes from the past or from the friend group. But in this movie the killers are the toxic fans of Sidney's book. Like just repeat the same formula. I know they try to make something new but you did this in Scream 4 and 5. In conclusion this new movie in the Scream franchise is nothing but a cheap cash grab movie."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "de3c570e-40e5-44a8-a045-c127f7f409d9", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184918", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "110d218f9c9bf83f19ed340bb901828dc1ab1f879e52bea21f1ff5266529377a"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "franp1982", "rating": 10, "date": "2026-02-27", "title": null, "content": "Scream 7 is a fantastic reconciliation of the franchise. It feels confident, emotional, and surprisingly mature while still delivering the meta-horror thrills we expect.\n\nThe emotional core between Neve Campbell and her on-screen daughter is genuinely powerful. There's a depth and vulnerability there that grounds the film and gives the stakes real weight. It's one of the strongest character dynamics the series has explored in years.\n\nGale is amazing - sharp, fearless, and completely in her element. Courteney Cox reminds us why she remains such an essential part of this franchise.\n\nAnd honestly? I didn't miss the Carpenter sisters at all. This story stands firmly on its own and proves the franchise is bigger than any one era.\n\nSome of the negative reviews feel more vindictive than critical, likely influenced by the controversy surrounding Melissa Barrera's departure. But if we judge the film purely on what's on screen, it's easily a 9 out of 10. The only thing holding it back from a perfect score is how rushed and short the ending feels.\n\nStill, Scream 7 is bold, emotional, and a worthy continuation of the legacy."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "232cf68e-7435-4b81-ab86-e9fbf9a96d0f", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184918", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "c7db10a8489288a5e006dc3dbce106dffa78f964ea49dc256046e0fc1c3c14de"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "eoinageary", "rating": 7, "date": "2026-02-28", "title": null, "content": "First and foremost, the review bombing on this movie is nuts, I am not reviewing the circumstances or any of the controversy surrounding Scream from 6 to 7, this is a review of the movie I just watched.\n\nWhen a new Ghostface killer emerges in the Pine view where Sidney Prescott (Neve Campbell) has built a new life, her darkest fears are realised as her daughter (Isabel May) becomes the next target. Determined to protect her family, Sidney must face the horrors of her past claiming to be Stu Mackey, and try to end the bloodshed, joined by some familiar faces to help her along the way.\n\nI won't lie, I was guessing the entire movie who were our killers because I couldn't nail anyone down. Stu was front and centre and I felt like that's where the past 2 movies were pushing us towards and of course there are always accomplices.\n\nThe kills were all really good, I felt ghostface was a lot spookier in this movie and going forward PLEASE keep it, ofc we get a lot of comedy but with ghostface it was eerie. Again good kills and good intensity from our first encounter with Sidney it's pretty much full throttle for the reminder of the movie.\n\nMusic was fine nothing crazy, visuals and sets were really good, dialogue a bit cheesy at times and to be completely honest thinking we were getting nostalgia ruled cameos it never felt like that, everyone felt in the right place.\n\nThis may be a hot take but I'd argue this is some of Sydney's better movies, I really enjoyed her in this one, not that I never did but for me 4 and 5 were meh with Sydney and how they utilised her while here she shines !\n\nSome negatives, her daughter was okay in the movie, she was a little weak but I understand to an extent that's the point she was never geared up for this. With that the final reveal bothered me I didn't find it satisfying at all the the movie was running an 8 at that point and would have slashed a 9 if it stuck the landing but for me it's been a while since we had a solid reveal and this wasn't it.\n\nOverall I really enjoyed this one, a big screen watch for sure, a guessing game and a spookier scream than normal, 7/10."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "66a3d7bb-44da-4da4-925d-4d71abac446c", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184918", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "4ad5f6889e2133b852d23b8f0c7d106d5299a8b4a2f0c5982fba33262d6a73e4"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "Brillfury", "rating": 3, "date": "2026-02-28", "title": null, "content": "Listen I'm 45, I've been a long-time fan of the SCREAM movies & I loved the fresh viewpoints of Scream 5 & 6 but this...this movie is beyond stupid. I will go ahead & say the best thing about it is Neve Campbell, she is amazing.\n\nThere is no hallmark Scream \"magic\", meaning humor or charm or anything. There are lots of lines and monologues that come off as CRINGE inducing. It's funny they made AI a theme of the film because the script itself definitely seems like AI wrote it.\n\nThe end reveal of the killers makes NO SENSE as in, the motivation explanations are STUPID. Almost insulting to the viewers intelligence.\n\nI really felt disappointed. This is a stupid movie, I don't care if they continue with the franchise after this, the magic is gone. It's very dull, very boring, very cringe.\n\nOh but I had Sour Patch kids as a treat while I watched and that was good."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "ff87bfd8-6d9c-471b-8134-9ff3df6a8ad1", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184918", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "a9521abe846b73323da2b34a85cd404e60ae4b3d631fd935794a6bd9862d2075"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "sirgarrykay", "rating": 10, "date": "2026-02-27", "title": null, "content": "THIS is what Scream 5 should have been. I was so excited for this movie and was hesitant that it wouldn't live up to the standards but boy it does. First of all the entire setting is just true autumn horror Wes Craven vibes. It's immaculately done. Nothing feels like it's on a stage (because most of it isn't!) and there are A TON of fighting, chasing, and stabbing throughout the entire movie. It picks up early on and stays steady with the action! The mother daughter duo is fantastic and really makes you excited for the fighter her daughter is going to become. I loved it. It was so Sidney and stayed true and really brought so much nostalgic factors. They talk about her past, and what happened in NYC and with Tatum. There's so much love to go around. You will be absolutely happy."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "09dfee32-c579-4c19-9fa4-824c89cb65b8", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184918", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "26de518741ae284719111b08f913f35e3ee5798abed4c01273faa22e7c21dd22"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "StolsReam", "rating": 1, "date": "2026-02-28", "title": null, "content": "Ok, so in this movie, Stu Macher manages to come back to life? It was on a facetime call about 3 or 2 times.. says he's at Sydney Prescott's (Evan's) daughter's school, now at a tavern.. then at the mid point of the movie, Sydney Prescott goes into her house and sees Dewey, Stu's mom and Stu himself... I never expected who the killers we're, just some blonde chick and a bald dude.. they used pretty much AI for Stu, Dewey and Stu's mom.. but I liked the gore at least."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "e851a4a7-3c77-4bd9-a6ce-ac7689e22930", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184918", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "82f89ab034d8e19bcb889260cb44db3362e1a10d563de270a40b457d7bbfd762"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "Maverick_1332", "rating": 7, "date": "2026-03-01", "title": null, "content": "You kind of know what you're going to get with these movies. If you've seen one you've basically seen them all and so if you buy a ticket expecting to a classic of the genre then you are going to end up being disappointed. I saw Scream 6 three years ago and have no real recollection of the plot. As it happens I learned after seeing this and then listening to a review that this movie is not connected to the previous due to fallouts when making the previous. I just accepted it as a standalone and enjoyed seeing Neve Campbell back on screen after her absence in 6. Does it make any sense? Well possibly not. Do a number of people appear to be able survive attacks with sharp implements that you think would put an end to an elephant? Well yes of course. Have I seen worse movies? Of course I have. So accept what it is and you won't be disappointed. The big question now is do they have the nerve to make a Scream 8. I think they do."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "d9139d7d-8ecd-41f0-9bcb-e9ddeea26c9a", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184918", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "2208523ef784f0230f6e666ddda814a099326a6d495d0ba3790cce19b46cdc18"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "mhtotalmoviefan", "rating": 7, "date": "2026-02-26", "title": null, "content": "As a longtime fan of the Scream franchise, even having a tattoo related to the saga, I have to say that this movie disappointed me in one very important aspect, however, it's a MUCH better movie than 5 and 6.\n\nI agreed with the original idea of Scream 3, indicating that Stu was alive. I like Matthew Lillard and his character Stu from Scream 1, because, for me, Stu is the most sinister, psychotic, and, incredibly, charismatic Ghostface. They chose the perfect actor for the guy. The marketing for this movie was almost entirely focused on Stu and his return, but the movie went down the path of teenagers. The movie deals with AI, and that really takes away the pulse and heart of the franchise. Stu was poorly used here.\n\nI was incredibly happy in the theater just to see Matthew Lillard back, and you could tell he was very excited playing Stu! It was actually chilling the first time he appeared here, it was surreal to see that in the cinema, but, in the end, it's all AI imagery. This approach is a suggestion from this new generation of internet teenagers who directly influenced the film's production to include this kind of nonsense.\n\nThe deaths here are brutal, the returning old characters continue to kick ass, the soundtrack is good, and the meta-language is great, but just the fact that they didn't bring Stu back makes it impossible to give it an 8 or higher. I got chills and was happy seeing Stu here, but discovering that it was all AI was disappointing. There are incredible scenes of investigation and threat here, like the one in the asylum, where it implies that he's really alive and exists, but, again, it's all AI. AT LEAST, they didn't show Stu's coffin, or his exhumed body.\n\nThe ghostface reveal here was interesting, albeit ridiculous. They put in two random characters who barely had enough screen time to be suspects, lol. The movie is worth it for Matthew Lillard and the creative deaths. I still don't understand how so many silly teenagers suddenly started liking this franchise in recent years."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "71b9ed2b-8dbf-4423-b387-e9015c050b1b", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184918", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "ac72229b1f039b2e22d9d33a461d0670a3d2ef1972b55ac10c1dff6dbf4a9943"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "andrewbrudenell1", "rating": 4, "date": "2026-03-02", "title": null, "content": "I thought Scream (2022) and Scream 6 both did a decent job of rebooting and reinvigorating the series but unfortunately this one just succeeds in booting it straight back into irrelevancy.\n\nThe Scream franchise after the first film is extremely self-referential; I get that and am largely fine with it. But Scream 7 just wallows in it. What feels like endless dreary and trite conversations about Sydney's inherited trauma and the impact on her children gives way to hollow fan service cameos from old characters and the pretty rote (if grisly) deaths of new characters that the film does even less than usual to establish.\n\nThen we're treated to Sydney and her daughter doing some truly cringeworthy girl-bossing all over the place for the last half hour and probably the weakest killer reveal/motive of the entire series. Gayle is inexplicably sidelined for the final act, which was actually fine with me as I find Courtney Cox's new face to be one of the scariest things left in this franchise.\n\nThe few high points were Jasmin Savoy Brown bringing some humour to the film in her supporting role and I guess the opening sequence with the Spring Hill house being turned into a tacky AirB&B experience for horror fans/lunatics is quite amusing.\n\nPlenty of plot holes; inlcuding the world's worst designed and under provisioned safe room but the whole thing is such a letdown that they hardly matter."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "0dacbfa5-26b7-4c10-b4b9-0240af8b7702", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184918", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "e7912baf478f63de8853aa7bda4a04c1b690e0a672df2650aa1eab4b4144b691"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "ch-stoerk", "rating": 1, "date": "2026-03-02", "title": null, "content": "This movie is offensively bad! I haven't rolled my eyeballs this far back into my skull since 'Jurassic World: Dominion'.\n\nThe opening scene is forgettable and lame. The new characters are hollow. Neve Campbell's performance feels phoned-in. The kills are dull and uninspired. Also, there are not enough of them. The killer reveal is laughably bad. The overreliance on nostalgia feels forced and sooooo lazy. The return of Stu Macher is wasted and goes nowhere. Honestly, do yourself a favour and pretend this movie doesn't exist!"}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "58db1db8-797b-4393-8dfd-8d687bd23f19", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184918", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "342061add3e6accddb13179d0b410c337cf680d02c02fc4f02c295cfb9ef0437"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "Itsdanielthompson", "rating": 7, "date": "2026-02-27", "title": null, "content": "Let's get the negative opinion out of the way right out of the gate - the reveal has no true value to it. No emotional connection, no shock, it's just.. meh. There, I said it. Probably my least favorite ghost face reveal to be honest. However, with that said, this is one of the most fun Scream installments in the franchise.\n\nYou can absolutely tell that Kevin Williamson was part of this movie, and Neve's performance proves exactly why shes worth all 7 million dollars they paid her to come back! This was also my favorite performance from Courtney Cox since the 4th film. Great pace, beautiful cinematography, fantastic opening scene and the numerous one liners from Sydney and Gale had the entire theatre laughing. Sydney kicks some serious ass in this movie as well!\n\nIn a nutshell, this was fun.. and that's what the scream movies have always been about. The last two installments were fun in their own way, but this takes us back to the original storyline, which is Sydney.. and I'm not mad about it.\n\nPoor reveal? Yes. Entertaining? Absolutely."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "4a5f6081-f337-48c5-b36f-6bc69ee258a1", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184918", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "dfe661b0f9f4bfae758937d841af4a8f0bb22fd91c601ced09c97e91a68f8461"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "ymrhqtrz", "rating": 4, "date": "2026-02-28", "title": null, "content": "As an avid scream fan, I was truly excited for this film. With the trailer hinting at the fact that Stu Macher could have survived somehow, I was compelled to see how this story would play out. Instead of that being the story, we got three cuckoo for Cocoa Puff killers (one escaped mental patient, another who was a patient and the third who was there for the ride) and whose motive was that they were displeased with the fact that Sidney Prescott stepped out of the spotlight and they wanted Tatum to become the new Sidney Prescott. How did this story even materialize? Who were the writers behind this? At this point they should've just kept going with the carpenter sisters and finished their stories. However, Neve Campbell and Courtney Cox were phenomenal as always and are literally the only reason for my rating.\n\nShould there be an 8th scream, I hope it's the final one in the series given the lazy story and writing from the 7th film. Unless they manage to somehow revitalize the franchise with the 8th film."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "bf960708-4880-4191-8b08-816fb4fb0f99", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184918", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "fb241cb753378ffbd17aad60c3cdf961d9ee536a3f25b15ad2b97997fb1dac00"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "nicolaelln-83746", "rating": 10, "date": "2026-02-27", "title": null, "content": "Scream 7 feels like a true love letter to the franchise. What I appreciated most were the clever references to past films and characters - they never felt forced or gimmicky, but instead added real emotional weight for longtime fans. There's a strong sense of legacy running throughout, and it respects the history of the series in a way that really works.\n\nI especially loved that the film shifted its focus back to Sidney and her family. Centering the story around her again gives it heart and grounding, reminding us why we became invested in this franchise in the first place. It feels personal, higher-stakes, and much more connected to the original spirit of the series.\n\nThe return of the classic music was another highlight. Hearing those familiar themes again added a huge wave of nostalgia and tension - it genuinely elevated some of the key scenes.\n\nThe ending did fall slightly flat for me. It wasn't bad by any means, but it didn't quite land with the impact I was hoping for. That said, the overall experience was strong, and in my opinion, it's a definite step up from Scream 5 and Scream 6. It feels more confident, more character-driven, and more in tune with what makes Scream special.\n\nOverall, a solid and satisfying entry that honors its roots while still moving forward.\n\nBRING ON SCREAM 8 BABY!"}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "1be990eb-dda1-4107-a1d8-8d0fe04a917c", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184918", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "6f846501b3cfdf47cd243f7f3fc7b66b03c738c980c39c0da9e237723e4b7685"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "FiveBy_5", "rating": 3, "date": "2026-02-27", "title": null, "content": "Nothing but fan service. Melissa & Jenna were the best parts of this resurrected franchise. Without them and their great storyline, this just serves up stale characters & things that were maybe cool 30 years ago. Predictable in every way. Could be easily exchanged for any other slasher with this one. Easily the worst sequel since 3."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "62a31fa0-18de-4af7-923d-640caf819093", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184918", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "7f28488916b8c8f65f062dc2d804ca3667d0e6bc2948086eeead9076f3834b1f"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "SpyroDungeon", "rating": 3, "date": "2026-02-28", "title": null, "content": "Scream 7 has some entertaining moments but wastes a lot of itself. There are a few good death scenes, but otherwise it progresses too quickly and is excessively monotonous, failing to offer much. I don't understand why they didn't continue with the previous storylines, and how the film ended up being so incomplete. Maybe Sidney has returned, that's the only hope, but unfortunately I didn't like it. It was rushed, everything felt like a hurried box office film."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "878e6cf8-ec46-4272-81a1-67ee9b0f3779", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184918", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "3fe3546a159bf71dec4d401913148259586ee20dbad374d96d1afd00405e36dc"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "Rigbo-4", "rating": 4, "date": "2026-02-27", "title": null, "content": "I love and adore all the Scream movies, some more than others but there's no bad scream movie, until this one.\n\nThere's no memorable set pieces (which is incredibly sad since the movie before had amazing set pieces), the opening sucked, all the new characters are so incredibly uninteresting and boring (including sidney's daughter although she gets better in act 3), and the killers are utterly awful.\n\nOnly positives I can say is that it had some good kills and the motive was okay."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "d534e502-49a3-4a94-9bd2-015b047ac725", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184918", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "a6efeec53d94a6db2212bb9aad134273924a545299d0078d574319cc9ab7dca9"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "Mk-0545", "rating": 1, "date": "2026-03-01", "title": null, "content": "When I saw Stu pop up on the screen I thought to myself: so this is what jumping the shark looks like.\n\nRegardless of how you feel about the Melissa Barrera situation. This movie feels like a hastily rewritten and her absence shows. There's a Melissa Barrera and jenna ortega size whole in this script.\n\nAnd after all that drama the movie they made is one the past scream films would have mocked."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "0a5f1fb5-e4b9-4cd1-87ce-8a0c8c876b43", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184918", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "5a5cbe656cf8319e7509c18c2a73c09a1868ef76ba4f8ad329046fdce6f60453"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "horrormoody", "rating": 7, "date": "2026-02-27", "title": null, "content": "The movie itself is not bad but it is nothing really new either. I think it was interesting to see Sidney in a mother role and how that played into the story. The kills are fun but the killer reveal was certainly a choice lol. I think they used Gale and Sydney the most effectively they have since the 4th installment and it was good to see them in action. Overall its a solid film thats worthy for the franchise and will satisfy many fans."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "65348bed-7587-4105-bc8d-d6e493d65580", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184918", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "9872160c97d796d911dee8f72352a6ce101c200669a432448e167711650a7d9c"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "ttmjngyi", "rating": 8, "date": "2026-02-26", "title": null, "content": "I was a little worried at first because i heard very mixed reviews about this. But after watching it myself, i can say that i totally loved it. It was so badass and brought back a bit of nostalgia, especially at the beginning when they showed the macher house! And when one of the killers came around the corner in slowmo? Banger lmao. But i gotta admit that i was slightly disappointed when they revealed who is behind ghostface. Other than that: perfection."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "c3df6a87-7530-430f-a19b-193a16ed9e20", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184918", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "055d99226503b698d50f2e25765bf6dbae05daa85418e0d955ae7b04ad894999"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "Hebysheree", "rating": 2, "date": "2026-02-25", "title": null, "content": "Please Please Please, don't let that franchise become the new Halloween with too many bad movies. What are we supposed to do with that one ? Nothing makes sense, the old cast looks tired and bored, the young cast is giving Disney Chanel made-for-tv-movie.\n\nKevin Williamson wrote a great sc\u00e9nario 30 years ago but that doesn't make him a good director, the reason why we love Scream was always because it's well directed, even when the sc\u00e9nario is men (hello Scream 4)."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "528c3bef-4965-479a-8b9e-5b01508ee2f2", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184918", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "aa0367a389696a8f31ebb7258a84646b2194c17a9a4da5dedb82755962013381"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "pranayjalvi", "rating": 4, "date": "2026-02-28", "title": null, "content": "Nothing more than a nostalgia induced entry into the franchise, Scream 7 is a shockingly shoddy film that is offensively bad. Adding insult to injury, the use of Deepfake/AI plot was lacklustre and very ridiculous.\n\nNot going through the plot, because it's always the same - Ghostface kills people again and the mystery to unravel the culprit behind. While the previous franchise didn't have a different story, the execution and narrative was atleast far better than this.\n\nFurthermore, the characters and their personalities were totally baffling, especially during the intense moments of face-offs. The decisions are stupid, the dialogues are mediocre. The only saving grace is Neve Campbell and Courtney Cox's cameo.\n\nWhile the story was already not going anywhere, the reveal was flatout dud. No impact, no strong motive, nothing. The movie was still okay when I was unaware of the culprit.\n\nOverall, Scream 7 is nothing but a cash grabber of a franchise that has a strong legacy with it's unique kills and characters. This time around, it was nothing but a mishap.\n\nMy Rating : 2/5."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "5d27e9c0-bf47-4fb3-a0d4-e4e92fd80ef0", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184918", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "b2c40752f4118663659c7cabffd903631db99016389fc947fcebee774987765e"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "FinalSmash1689", "rating": 7, "date": "2026-03-01", "title": null, "content": "PROS: -The opening sequence was fun.\n\n-Neve Campbell is fantastic. Loved seeing Sidney as a Mom.\n\n-Ghostface is brutal here! RIP Mckenna Grace.\n\n-The tone really matches the Wes Craven films.\n\n-Isabel May gives a great performance as Tatum.\n\n-This is a Mother/Daughter story at its core. A first for this franchise.\n\n-Always fun to see Gale Weathers.\n\nCONS: -The Ghostface reveal/motive is horrendous.\n\n-The 3rd act left a lot to be desired.\n\n-Gale has nerve damage from the last film, but Chad is somehow perfectly okay.\n\nI really enjoyed this experience. I'm not a big horror fan but I make an exception for the Scream franchise. The first three movies really were a cultural touchstone of the '90s that, even watching these new movies, kind of takes me back there. Seeing Sidney as a Mother and Wife was really refreshing. I loved seeing her happy instead of her being a traumatized victim. Neve Campbell does a great job of letting her history live in her character without it overshadowing her life. Scream is Sidney's story at its core, and it was smart move to make her the central figure again. I also liked that this is the first movie to be a Mother/Daughter story. Tatum's struggle to get her mom to open up about who she is while Sidney is trying to protect her from her past was an emotionally grounded conflict that worked for both characters. Ghostface (pre-reveal) was brutal here. Burning people alive, spilling guts across an auditorium and taking out four people in a bar, Ghostface came to play! However, the reveal of the killers and the motive was extremely weak and contrived. I feel if they rewrote the last act, this could've cracked my top three Scream movies. Regardless of that, I had a good time at the movies. I got exactly what I came to see and for a franchise that's now seven movies in, that's exactly what I was hoping for. 7/10."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "10930175-5e77-4175-b22d-b671e5abe0b8", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184918", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "ce98c5066ecf2e7f3e923fb8ffe285024e88436dac7e838e94b4476596168489"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "TheFilmDetective", "rating": 7, "date": "2026-02-26", "title": null, "content": "Scream 7 wastes no time diving into chaos. The film centers on a new wave of terror as Ghostface resurfaces with even more calculated brutality. This time, the murders feel more personal, more vicious, and far less restrained. The movie embraces its slasher roots unapologetically the kills are graphic, tense, and staged with unsettling creativity. Longtime fans will appreciate how the film balances classic suspense building sequences with sudden, stomach-dropping violence.\n\nUnlike some of the more polished entries in the franchise, this chapter has a darker, meaner tone. The humor is still present self aware and biting but it never undercuts the horror. The result is a film that feels intense from beginning to end.\n\nIf you're looking for a true bloody typical slasher movie, then this is all Scream 7 definitely is.\n\nThe practical effects stand out, with realistic makeup and visceral attack scenes that don't shy away from showing the damage Ghostface leaves behind. Several sequences are genuinely brutally shocking not just because of who dies, but how they die. Scream 7 pushes the franchise's violence further than before, making it one of the most brutal entries in the series but like most of the scream movies in the franchise this has the same kind of tone and again can you guess the killer ?"}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "1b6388b2-bd7d-4053-8072-5b4e9753775b", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184918", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "10b4090e6e93bfb4dbef8e46faebb1094a6ffaeebde69c17c58887a89cbe7779"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "mozartcrb", "rating": 2, "date": "2026-03-04", "title": null, "content": "The reveal was weak. The motive was weak. Some of the nostalgia was fun. Some of the kills were fun. Even the intro made no sense to me whatsoever. Again what's the motivation there? It was fun seeing Neve as Sydney and they should have tied things more to Stu. AI was just a waste of a red herring.\n\nAlso, the three killers were barely on screen, and their motivation again was very weak. It made no sense whatsoever.\n\nAnother pet peeve of these movies is I'm sorry but no one dies anymore. They all survive after being stabbed multiple times that's just lame. There's no way that the husband would've survived nor the kids in the bar, but this franchise has gotten old and stale."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "646f4a27-09d4-4d80-a086-629ab7ee7933", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184918", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "a78db1fac00a3e20cab97d67105f281f34bd7115d5ccbaee7f7c6669f1761817"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "cantrelayne", "rating": 7, "date": "2026-02-28", "title": null, "content": "Always the original 3 Screams will be the best and this movie goes to show, once again, why the original cast will always be the best, even when they age.\n\nScreams 4 - 6 where a waste of time, money and effort. All the re - hash, re -told, re -\"imagined\", re - stupid words whatever will NEVER be as good as the original. Whilst the original cast members continue to prove they are the best, this movie is not witty, fast paced and fun as the original 3; it is by far a good story compared to 4 - 6. The young cast members were irrelevant and basically just props. Matthew Lillard and Neve Campbell are the reasons to watch this, as Courtney Cox is no longer recognizable. It's an interesting story, even though the \"big reveal\" is just stupid. It gets 7 for Matthew, Neve and the story. The ending gets a 0. Go watch the first 3 and remember why we're still talking about it 30 years on."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "fc68ee99-b01d-4b94-bfbf-06d7926336ae", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184918", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "d8999ddc99caa7762cc2ca24c534b330f62c35b63e4c20c994bfba48ce784a62"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "Codymileswoodruff", "rating": 4, "date": "2026-03-04", "title": null, "content": "As somebody in their mid 30s who's seen the first 6 numerous times, I was ready to see what 7 had in store. Especially with the changes that happened. Unfortunately, when the script changed, the writers must have changed as well.\n\nThe move started out okay, I liked the opening scene well enough. My 2 favorite deaths were McKenna and the boy with the beer. Others felt rushed or not well thought out like Celeste in the bar. The twins were absolutely pointless in this movie. In the other two, they both endured much more and kept pushing. In this one, one small shoulder stab and one stomach slash took them down for the count? And Gale gets left in the news station only to turn up again in the conclusion? No Kirby at all? No mention of Sam and Tara like they didn't exist?\n\nI would have rather waited longer for the movie to come out, instead of having whatever this nonsense was that was pushed through production. I hope if there's an 8, whoever the writers are do a much better job of getting this franchise back on track."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "93f95b51-cff6-42d7-b704-0ac05fdcb668", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184918", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "8902eee47aec1e6b21dd3754e819f9ec2a0970755bcc09a6cbef981cc3c858de"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "KoenWellins", "rating": 10, "date": "2026-03-02", "title": null, "content": "Scream 7 is the latest scream film, and thankfully I got to watch this in cinemas. I enjoyed it heaps, despite in my opinion being one of the weaker entries in the franchise, I still don't believe there is such thing as a bad Scream movie. The only thing I somewhat have a problem with is the lighting, I found a bit too dark, but besides that, of course I'm going to love watching Sydney Evans (previously Sydney Prescott) being her badass self. One thing though that does feel out of place in this movie is the use of A. I., which feels too modern to be in it, but it's alright I guess. Even though the Carpenter sisters, Sam (Melissa Barrera) and Tara (Jenna Ortega), aren't present in the film, due to, in short, political differences. But that's alright, we still have Sydney, Gale, Mindy and Chad, so I'm going to love it regardless. Plus cameos a plenty, including from Matthew Lillard, who is kinda a horror legend.\n\nOverall, I love this movie, and you should to. I highly recommend you see it in cinemas if it is still in cinemas if your reading this pretty early. Great film, go see it!"}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "bda1d002-f1f7-4b90-9182-dc1678facb53", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184918", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "1798d703d71f001f3dd1dfaefab61a645e74add3179ea712f98c7f1349ef8c66"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "Almir25", "rating": 10, "date": "2026-02-25", "title": null, "content": "Scream 7 is, in my opinion, one of the better slasher movies in recent years, and I honestly don't understand why some people are hating on it for no real reason. The movie is exactly what Scream is supposed to be, tense, brutal, fast paced and full of suspense. There's plenty of action and blood, several intense chase scenes, solid jump scares and that constant feeling that no character is truly safe.\n\nPeople shouldn't expect a big budget action spectacle like a Tom Cruise blockbuster with over the top stunts and explosions, because Scream has never been that. This franchise has always been about a masked killer, psychological mind games, mystery, paranoia, twists and trying to figure out who is behind the mask. That's exactly what this movie delivers, and it does it in a way that feels energetic and engaging.\n\nThe pacing is strong and there aren't many slow or boring moments. The tension builds nicely and there's always a sense that something is about to happen. One small criticism would be the use of AI within the movie, even though it wasn't used for the franchise itself but as part of the story, it still feels slightly unnecessary. Also, the ending could have been handled differently. The killers could have been different characters, and their motives weren't the strongest, their arguments for why they were killing felt a bit weak. With a more convincing final reveal, the film would have been even better.\n\nIn the end, this is a movie that really delivered and proved the franchise still has something to offer. The energy is strong, the atmosphere is dark, and the sense of tension lasts through most of the runtime. It definitely has a few flaws, especially in the final act, but that doesn't take away from how entertaining and intense it is to watch. Overall, it's a solid sequel that keeps your attention and leaves an impression even after the credits roll."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "82606e60-6012-4e9a-817a-037f9254f27a", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184918", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "1b6f23bcf3c897b977751f07d5c629a4cc8decd909af9cd1787fefe1fc166c96"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "Overtheredskies", "rating": 8, "date": "2026-02-27", "title": null, "content": "I went in with super low expectations, expected a basic film...what we get is the Ultimate slasher film! This is real cinema...It sucks you in and plays with all of your emotions...is it a silly slasher? Sure...but it's also a great one...Scream doesnt get any better than this...you know it's a good one when you go home after seeing the movie and you FEEL like Ghostface could be creepin around in your own home...I love how all the 100s of youtubers and Instagramers predictions I've heard and seen were all WR0NG! Everybody was wrong about ending and everything! Neve Campbell and Courtney Cox are better than ever. Oh and who's Melissa Barerra? Who's Jenna Ortega? Never heard of em."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "a21901eb-31cf-48fa-95f8-2044704399eb", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184918", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "7d07e9e5756986535ce0c0987994193d17b26247700296ab2f1c2851e9f7a956"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "pipkorn", "rating": 4, "date": "2026-03-02", "title": null, "content": "Let's talk about the good: The twins are great but they were such a small part of this movie they shouldn't have been in it. They should have just saved them for another movie and just made them the new stars of the franchise.\n\nThe bad: They had one job! They had the legacy final girl they had the legacy ghost face (not as a force ghost) and they dropped the ball. I get ML is getting old, they all are but they could have gone with the cult of ghost face and had him guiding 2-5 ghost faces then dropped another tv on his head but the wasted their chance. So many fans wanted this and they pulled a deep fake on us. I almost walked out. I'm honestly never going to see another one of these in theaters."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "9ecfdee4-de27-4720-b58b-b0b8e5c34181", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184918", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "eb15b50a70fb014afbfb4ee793b883a74abaf20f71194aefa2295ed4a6975841"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "nERDbOX_Dave", "rating": 7, "date": "2026-02-28", "title": null, "content": "There's something poetic about opening Scream 7 at the Macher house (now an Airbnb) where horror fans can literally rent nostalgia for the weekend. It's a clever idea on paper. Scott, a diehard Stab fanatic, thinks it's the perfect getaway for him and his girlfriend. Instead, it becomes the franchise's most fiery opening yet. Ghostface doesn't just kill, he torches the house. It's loud, aggressive, and a statement: this isn't the same Scream.\n\nWe shift from Woodsboro to Pine Grove, a quieter town where Sidney Prescott-Evans has built a life away from the trauma. Neve Campbell slips back into Sidney with ease, resilient, layered, and still carrying that quiet storm behind her eyes. This time, the nightmare hits closer than ever as her daughter, Tatum Evans (played by Isabel May), becomes Ghostface's next target.\n\nThe emotional core should be airtight. A mother protecting her daughter from the very horror that shaped her life? That's powerful territory.\n\nBut here's where things get complicated.\n\nFrom the jump, the cinematography signals change. Gone are the sweeping wide shots that made us scan every corner of the frame. In their place: tighter, cleaner, almost glossy \"big Hollywood\" framing. The pacing is relentless, once we meet Tatum, Ben, Hannah, Chloe, Lucas, and the rest, the film never really slows down.\n\nOn first watch, that stylistic shift pulled me out. It didn't feel like Scream. On second watch, I appreciated the boldness but that doesn't mean it always works.\n\nThe movie almost dares you to keep up. Ghostface reveals themselves in calculated, taunting fashion, practically announcing attacks with a \"try and stop me\" energy. It's different. It's aggressive. It's less whodunit and more crime drama.\n\nAnd that's where longtime fans may feel the friction. Especially since one of the key things to this franchise, is Roger Jackson's voice, taunting his prey throughout the film. That is severely lacking here.\n\nThe kills? Brutal. Possibly the most savage in franchise history. There's no denying the technical craftsmanship, the violence hits hard and doesn't flinch. But brutality without emotional investment lands hollow.\n\nMany of the new characters feel underdeveloped. When things happen to them, the impact just isn't there. In past films, even side characters had enough texture to make their deaths sting. Here, some feel like narrative placeholders.\n\nThe reveal? Well-acted. Confident. But logically? It doesn't quite add up. It's not controversial because it's bold... it's confusing because the math doesn't math. Continuity issues and plot threads introduced without payoff make the finale feel like \"2 + 2 = potato.\" You want to lean in, but pieces just don't connect.\n\nLegacy character wise. Gale, Mindy, and Chad are present, but underutilized. They feel more like connective tissue than driving forces. For a franchise built on honoring its survivors, that absence is noticeable.\n\nThis is a statement film. It's the studio essentially saying: we're moving forward whether you're ready or not. And that's a risky move.\n\nScream 7 doesn't feel like a love letter to the past. It feels like a pivot point. A tonal and structural shift toward something new, more procedural, more direct, less meta-wink and slasher-rule dissection.\n\nAs someone who dissects marketing, who lives in the details, I'll be honest, the studio's attempts to misdirect (fake sounds, Stu teases, visual red herrings) were ambitious, but fans are detectives. The breadcrumbs added up quicker than they expected.\n\nI left the theater with mixed emotions. I still have them after two viewings. There's ambition here. There's brutality. There's a clear new direction.\n\nThe question isn't whether it's good or bad.\n\nThe question is: Is this still Scream?\n\nAnd I'm not entirely sure yet.\n\nBut I am curious what comes next."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "ec8805d2-38cc-493f-b20a-c8019c1c573d", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184918", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "eac51f0482605a466d88cdc4618d3189538468a7b8bcb8fffb49810774ade270"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "CXS23", "rating": 10, "date": "2026-03-01", "title": null, "content": "Okay if you're reading the reviews to decide whether you want to see part 7 or not i recommend just watching it! Most of the reviews are coming from haters who are mad about Melissa being fired she made a decision and she faced the consequences of her actions that shouldn't be held against all the other actors in the scream movies! I don't want to give any spoilers but I want to let you guys know scream 7 has a lot of action it's funny and I personally enjoyed it and felt Kevin Williams brought his characters back to doing what they do best! Now 7 is a little bit more serious than the original 3 movies but it still has the scream charm! Sidney Prescott has great character development and she's become a really strong woman and now she's a mother and that dynamic is very cool to see! Please just watch it and ignore the negativity!"}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "6e92b86e-ce2f-46c6-b584-a5d02eab4f03", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184918", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "881e4884a2339abca40072bd82ae27c3feed3f3ce921be16e56b9703aee90f1f"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "UniqueParticle", "rating": 9, "date": "2026-02-28", "title": null, "content": "I pre ordered my ticket 3 weeks in advance for imax - Glad it that option no other Scream had better format I'm pretty sure. Amazing for nostalgia, awesome cast, great directing from legendary Kevin Williamson and enthralling entertainment at least to me! Maybe only a few bumpy moments that I'd understand the hate but overall very satisfying - Definitely better than previous ones!"}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "92b9338d-ce56-43db-baf0-ca60236cbeb6", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184918", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "91a8a85caac8ac8531be24ae124dbde5cd4f6a7ce37318eba5c5ded798880cbd"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "EvanparkerT", "rating": 8, "date": "2026-03-01", "title": null, "content": "It's pretty iconic how the DGG Halloween trilogy mirrored the structure of the original three films and now the new modern Scream entries seem to reflect the course of the original trilogy as well both critically and behind the scenes production.\n\nScream 7 brings a familiar presence back to the forefront in a way that feels fresh and elevated, something that felt missing during the Radio Silence era. The film shifts the focus back to genre commentary that extends beyond the Stab movies themselves, rather than leaning on recycled twists or familiar locations. It plays like a natural continuation of Scream 4, with Sidney's book serving as a meaningful driver of the central plot.\n\nUnlike its predecessor, the set pieces here feel motivated by story rather than spectacle. The commentary on parasocial relationships feels timely and culturally relevant and while there is still some plot armor, it's dialed back enough that the stakes feel more believable.\n\nThat said, the film isn't without its issues. Some character returns feel a bit gimmicky and lean heavily into fan service, though a few are handled far better than others. Gale, for example, feels like more than a stock character this time, she has purpose and emotional weight within the narrative. Chad and Mindy are allowed to have distinct identities and their sibling dynamic comes across as natural. And of course, Sidney feels completely in her prime here, commanding, layered, and central in a way the franchise has needed for years. The third act is the weakest act, but at least it avoids feeling derivative and the performances remain grounded enough to keep you immersed.\n\nI have a feeling Scream 7 may become the new Scream 3, a sequel that was initially divisive but ultimately reappraised more kindly with time."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "bb7c1156-6d37-4d14-9cc9-0180ad31537c", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184918", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "5f4604bca418fc1dafb6cd074a1fbbf7fdf0eb0ffb5aa173108b0ec286f985c1"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "cherokeysong", "rating": 8, "date": "2026-02-27", "title": null, "content": "30 years after Wes Craven's Scream was released, the seventh installment in the beloved franchise comes at a time when the adrenaline-inducing slasher film takes more than just a scary masked figure to move an audience. It is unarguable that the 1996 film resuscitated the horror sub-genre, and while this latest addition is predictable according even to its own classic rules, it is a good lesson to other franchises and reboots on how to keep the fans happy. Neve Campbell makes a welcome comeback as Sidney Prescott, and we are essentially waterboarded with her character for nearly two hours, as the Lord intended for this franchise. While other reboots have floundered in recent years due to the introduction of unfamiliar \"newbie\" characters and a significantly reduced screen time for the legacy characters, Scream 7 takes us back to the roots of what made us love Ghostface and Woodsboro and the Buck 120 knife in the first place. Would this film be anything special as a standalone slasher? Probably not, but it is clear that Kevin Williamson wrote/directed this as a nod to the Sidney Prescott devotees. After the entertaining but arguably somewhat aimless Scream 6, 7 feels like a kind of homecoming."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "dacad0e5-5010-4854-bba3-7606d8749e2a", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:04.184918", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "503a0f6550706b51aa10a7b86e238d9dc5972eb3d5a56641b9586a82dc7c74e6"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27047903", "author": "iZombieCat", "rating": 5, "date": "2026-02-27", "title": null, "content": "Scream 7 isn't the worst movie in the world, but it is definitely dumb. You can definitely tell this movie was held together with tape. All of the original cast performances were great, of course - including Matthew Lillard as \"Stu Macher.\"\n\nBut the story is absolutely all over the place. I know the two lead actresses were going to be out, but this movie had potential. The other two leads from 5 and 6 feel like nobody cameo side characters after two movies of buildup. I would even say this movie's marketing campaign and teasers of \"Stu Macher\" almost feel like false advertisement. The main reason I bought a ticket was to see how they would bring Stu into the picture, just for it to feel like I got cheated and lied to.\n\nIf you are a Scream fan, there is enjoyment to be had. But if you weren't already, this one definitely isn't going to win you over."}}
